The Five-element doctrine illustrates the connections existing between all things by the relationship of inter-generation and inter-restriction among the five elements. It holds that nothing is in an isolated or static state, that is, everything is in a state of harmonious balance maintained by the constant motion of inter-generation and inter-restriction.
Ancient thinkers found in actual practice that there exists in nature such a universal phenomenon; one thing often closely followed by another or one thing positively influenced by another, thus they formulated the theory of generation in the five elements.
The regular order of generation in the five elements is: wood generates fire, fire does earth, earth does metal, metal does water, and water in turn generates wood.
The regular order for the restriction in the five elements is: wood restricts earth, earth does water, water does fire, fire does metal, and metal in turn restricts wood.
For example, excessive wood may over-restrict earth, resulting in insufficiency of earth so called "wood encroaches earth".
For instance, wood should be restricted by metal, however when wood is excessively strong, it is not restricted by metal, on the contrary, restricts metal, which is known as"wood violates metal".
(3) Earth has the property of generating, transforming and receiving. (4) Metal has the property of purifying, descending and astringing, (5) Water has the property of nourishing and flowing downwards.
It is applied mainly to excess-syndrome with mother-child relationship.
For instance, an excess-syndrome due to exuberance of the liver-fire can be treated by purging the fire of the heart (child-organ of the liver), because purgation of the heart-fire helps to reduce the liver-fire.
In acupuncture, in the case of an excess-syndrome of the mother organ, points pertaining to the child-channel are needled with purging manipulation.
For instance, in the treatment of excess syndrome of the liver, either Shaofu or Xingjian is to be needled.
Here water refers to the kidneys, while wood to the liver.
This is a method of replenishing and restoring the lung (metal) Qi by invigorating the spleen (earth) and replenishing Qi.
It is indicated in deficiency of the lungs and spleen caused by failure of the spleen and stomach to nourish the lungs.
It is usually used to treat edema and distention resulting from the overflow of pathogenic water dampness due to dysfunction of the spleen.
Here wood and earth refer respectively to the liver and spleen.
This is a method of treating hyperfunction of the liver and insufficiency of the spleen by soothing the liver and invigorating the spleen, which as the method of dispersing the stagnated liver-Qi or calming the liver to normalize the stomach-Qi or coordinating between the liver and spleen.
It is indicated for the relief of hyperactivity of the liver (wood) which over-restricts the spleen (earth).
Here metal and wood separately represent the lungs and liver.
This is a method of checking hyperactivity of the liver by purifying the lung-Qi also called the method of purifying the lungs to reduce the liver, which is indicated in exuberance of the liver-fire caused by the failure of the lung-Qi to keep pure and descent.
Zhang Jingyue, a famous physician in the Ming Dynasty said in his Classified Canon (Leijing):"Zang implies storage;...... while Xiang, figure and appearance.
Since viscera are located within the body and their phase is observed from the outside of the body, these two characters"Zang" and"Xiang" put together denote phase of viscera".
The Zang-organ was described in Huangdi Neijing as an internal organ for storing and reserving.
The common physiological property of the five Zang-organs is to produce and store vital essence.
The common functional property of the six Fu-organs is to take in, transport and transform foodstuffs.
Like the six Fu-organs morphologically, they are hollow in shape; and like the Zang-organs functionally, they have the ability to store vital essence, but inability to take in and transport foodstuffs. They are, therefore, called extraordinary Fu-organs.
The heart possesses two main functions, namely, the control of blood and vessels and the regulation of mental activities.
It has its body opening in the tongue, its outward manifestations on the face, its particular emotion in joy and its associated secretion in sweat.
Repletion of the heart-Qi can maintain normal strength, rate and rhythm of the heart.
On the contrary, if the heart-Qi is insufficient, various cardiovascular diseases may ensue.
They are also the passageway through which blood circulates.
In a narrow sense, it refers to mental activities controlled by the heart, such as spirit, consciousness and thinking.
In modern physiology, all these are thought of as the physiological functions of the cerebrum or its reflection of outward things,
Usually, joy is a response to external favorable stimuli beneficial to the heart's performance of the function of governing blood and vessels. As a result, the vessels are made unblocked and Qi-blood harmonized.
However, excessive joy tends to impair the functioning of the heart.
As far as the heart's function of controlling mental activities is concerned, there are two kinds of pathological changes: hyperactivity and hypoactivity. Generally, the former gives rise to incessant laughing, and the latter to sorrow.
The connection of vessels by the heart implies that the movement of blood vessels in the body is dominated by the heart.
The heart has its outward manifestations on the face, which is extremely rich in blood vessels. Thus, the physiological functions of the heart can be detected through the changes in both colour and luster on the face.
For instance, when the heart-Qi is exuberant and the blood supply is sufficient, the complexion will be rosy and lustrous; while insufficiency of the heart-Qi will lead to pale and dark-turbid complexion; deficiency of blood, to pallid complexion; and stagnation of blood, to darkish or purplish face.
The discharge of sweat relies upon the opening-closing action of defensive Qi on the striae of skin and muscles. When the striae are open, the sweat is let out; while they are closed, no sweating occurs.
The sweat is transformed from body fluids, and, what is more, blood and body fluids are derived from food and drink, as the saying goes:"Blood and sweat are from the same source".
The former is governed by the heart, and the latter is said to be "the fluid of the heart".
Moreover, the tongue is also richly supplied with blood vessels.
On the contrary, if the heart fails to work properly, its physiological and pathological changes can also be reflected on the tongue.
Consequently, the functional state of the heart can often be detected through observation of the tongue.
Qi counterflow syndrome often involves the lungs, stomach and liver, including upward counterflow of lung-Qi, stomach-Qi and liver-Qi.
The lungs, equivalent to "metal" of the five elements, are the house of soul and dominator of Qi.
The latter denotes that the lungs are visceral organs where interchange of Qi inside and outside the body takes place, i.e., the exchange of gases between the body and its environment occurs through the breathing movements of the lungs.
The former is a two-fold process concerned basically with the formation of pectoral Qi and the-regulation of Qi of the whole body.
The dispersing function of the lungs consists mainly in the following:(1) discharging the stale gas from the body by its functional activities;(2) distributing the food essence and body fluids transported by the spleen to all parts of the body and to the skin and its hairs externally; and (3) spreading defensive Qi so as to control the opening-closing action of the striae of skin and muscles, thereby converting the metabolized body fluids into sweat to be removed from the body. The descending function of the lungs, on the other hand, lies in:(1) inspiring fresh air from the external environment;(2) sending down the fresh air inspired and the body fluids as well as food essence transported from the spleen; and (3) purifying the foreign bodies in the lungs and the respiratory tract in order to keep the latter clean.
The lungs can regulate this process by maintaining normal flow, distribution and discharge of body fluids due to their dispersing and descending functions.
By their dispersing function the lungs not only spread body fluids and food essence to all parts of body, but also control the discharge of sweat as well as the opening-closing action of the striae of skin and muscles. By their descending function the lungs send down fresh air into the kidneys, and also continuously send down a part of body fluids, which was converted into urine to be excreted from the body under the functioning of the kidneys and urinary bladder,
By convergence of blood vessels in the lungs is meant that all the blood flows along the vessels to all parts of the body through the lungs where the exchange of gases takes place.
The circulation of blood relies upon the impulsion of Qi and with the lifting-lowering of Qi the blood flows to all parts of the body.
This function may be summarized as follows:(1) the lungs make rhythmic breathing movements;(2) by means of their breathing movements, the lungs regulate the functioning of Qi of the whole body, or the lifting-lowering and entering-exiting movements of Qi;(3) they assist the heart in promoting and regulating blood circulation; and (4) they help to maintain normal flow, distribution and discharge of body fluids.
Actually, this function is fully reflected in the above main jobs done by the lungs.
After all, melancholy and sorrow are the emotional responses to unfavorable 『 stimuli, bringing about a consuming effect on the Qi of the body.
As the lungs dominate Qi, melancholy and sorrow are apt to impair the lungs.
On the other hand, when the lungs are deficient, the body's tolerance to unfavorable stimuli is diminished and melancholy or sorrow is likely to occur.
The skin with its hairs must be warm-nourished and moist-replenished by defensive Qi and body fluids respectively, thus forming a protective barrier against external pathogens.
Conversely, the invasion of the skin and its hairs by foreign pathogenic agents causes closure of the striae of skin and muscles with stagnation of defensive Qi, frequently followed by failure of the lung-Qi to disperse and descend, which, in turn, leads to such pathological changes as occlusion of the striae of skin and muscles, stagnation of defensive Qi and so on.
In case of an attack of the lungs by pathogenic cold, the lucid nasal discharge flows from the nose; in case of an attack by heat the nasal discharge becomes yellowish-thick; and in case of an invasion by dryness, the nasal cavity becomes dry.
The sense of smell and pronunciation in the larynx are both concerned with the lung-Qi.
The sound lung-Qi with smooth breathing is accompanied by a keen sense of smell and sonorous voice.
If foreign pathogens which invade the lungs come mostly from the nose and larynx, such symptoms as stuffy nose, running nose, sneezing, itching of the throat, hoarseness and aphonia may occur as a result.
Its main physiological functions are:(1) to transport, transform and send up the nutrients, and. (2) to keep the blood flowing in the vessels.
Since the nutrients transported and transformed by the spleen and stomach are used for production of Qi-blood and body fluids as well as for maintenance of life activities of the body, the spleen and stomach as"the source of Qi-blood"are also known as"the material basis of the acquired constitution".
The spleen which opens into the mouth and has its outward manifestations on the lips, corresponds to earth according to the theory of the five elements.
This function of the spleen involves digestion of food and drink and absorption and transportation of the nutrients contained in them.
It is chiefly manifested by transportation and transformation of the essential substances from drink as well as from foodstuffs.
By the transporting-transforming action of the spleen on the foodstuffs is meant that the foodstuff in the stomach is digested, its nutrients are absorbed and then distributed to all parts of the body.
All of the above-mentioned processes are achieved under the control of the spleen. If the spleen functions normally, the organism can obtain adequate nutrients to maintain its normal functioning.
Conversely, if the spleen fails to carry on its functions of transportation and transformation, normal digestion and absorption of foodstuffs do not take place and there occurs instead such a morbid condition marked by abdominal distension, diarrhea, poor appetite, lassitude, emaciation, or even other symptoms due to insufficient Qi-blood supply.
By the transporting-transforming action of the spleen on water we mean the spleen's function of absorbing, conveying and spreading body fluids. That is to say, the spleen can in time transport the fluids absorbed from food and drink to the lungs to be distributed to all parts of the body, thereby fulfilling its nourishing-moistening role.
On the contrary, dysfunction of the spleen in transporting-transforming fluids will lead to retention of body fluids and development of the pathological changes mentioned above, or even to edema.
This function of the spleen refers to all processes concerned with the absorption of nutrients from food and drink and their upward transport to the heart, lungs, head and eyes. In the meantime, these nutrients are transformed into Qi-blood to nourish the whole body by the action of the heart and lungs.
The ability to send nutrients upward is the functional feature of the spleen just as that to send digested food downward is the functional property of the stomach. When this function of the spleen is carried on properly, the nutrients from food and drink can be absorbed and conveyed normally, and plenty of vital Qi eventually makes the body full of vigour and vitality. In addition, the spleen has the function of keeping the internal organs in their fixed positions.
If inability of the spleen to uplift re. sults in sinking of the spleen-Qi, there may appear such pathological changes as prolapse of rectum due to protracted diarrhea, or even prolapse of other internal viscera.
This function refers to the spleen's capacity to keep the blood flowing within vessels and prevent it from extravasating.
The main mechanism of the spleen's control of blood flow is attributable to the commanding action of the spleen-Qi on blood circulation and is closely related to its capacity as the source of growth and development of Qi-blood.
Though anxiety is considered as the emotion of the spleen, it is concerned with the function of the heart in controlling mental activities as well.
Moderate anxiety doesn't exert any unfavorable influence on physiological functions of the organism. However, excessive anxiety or failure in an attempt may disturb its proper functioning, thus resulting in such pathological manifestations as stagnation and depression of Qi.
If Qi is depressed in the middle-Jiao due to excessive anxiety, such symptoms as anorexia, epigastric stuffiness and distress, dizziness, etc, are likely to occur due to impairment of the spleen's function to transport, transform and send up nutrients.
Therefore, the development and strength of the muscles of the body are related to the function of the spleen and stomach in transport. For instance, if the spleen and stomach fail to function properly, the muscles will become emaciated, weak, and even paralysed.
Its functions are. to moisten the oral cavity, to protect the mucous membrane of the mouth, and to help to swallow and digest food.
In case of incoordination between the spleen and stomach, saliva will increase rapidly and profusely, and spontaneous salivation will ensue as a consequence. For this reason, saliva is referred to as the secretion of the spleen.
When the spleen and stomach function properly in transport, taste and appetite will be normal.
On the contrary, dysfunction of the spleen in transport may give rise to abnormal tastes, such as tastelessness, sweet taste with sticky sensation in the mouth, and hence poor appetite.
The colour and lustre of the lips depend on the adequate supply of Qi-blood transported by the spleen. Therefore, the functional state of the spleen is reflected on the colour and lustre of the lips.
The liver is situated at the right hypochondriac region below the diaphragm in the abdomen.
It is the house of mood, the storehouse of blood and the controller of tendons as well. It corresponds to wood in the five elements and is characterized by ascending-spreading movement.
Its main physiological functions are concerned with the control of normal flow of Qi and the storage of blood.
The liver is a solid visceral organ responsible for ascending-spreading movement, which is regarded as the physiological basis for its control of normal flow of Qi.
This function of the liver is an important link in regulating functional activities of Qi and promoting circulation of blood and body fluids.
(1) It regulates functional activities of Qi, by which are meant here its lifting-lowering and entering-exiting movements. The liver plays a part in regulating and balancing the lifting-lowering and entering-exiting movements of Qi.
Conversely, dysfunction of the liver may manifest itself by two kinds of morbid conditions, hyperactivity and hypoactivity.
In the latter case, the functioning of Qi must be impeded and may bring about distending pain of the chest, hypochondrium, breasts or lower abdomen, and mental depression, etc; in the former case, there may occur such pathological changes as upward adverse flow of the liver-Qi, characterized by distending pain of head and eyes, flushed face with congested eyes, irritability, restlessness, and so on, or upward overflow of blood due to adverse flow of Qi, marked by hematemesis, hemoptysis and even sudden syncope with unconsciousness.
(2) It promotes the transporting-transforming function of the spleen and stomach.
As the bile is the aggregation of the surplus liver-essence, normal functioning of the liver leads to regular secretion and excretion of the bile, thus facilitating the function of the spleen and stomach in transportation and transformation of nutrients.
On the contrary, stagnation of the liver-Qi will bring about irregular secretion and excretion of the bile and further impair the function of the spleen and stomach in transportation and transformation.
Therefore, the normal functioning of the liver will lead to normal functional activities of Qi, harmony of Qi-blood and proper functioning of the five Zang-organs, thus, resulting in normal emotional activities.
This function is concerned with the liver's capability in storing blood and regulating the volume of circulating blood.
If the liver fails to function properly in storing blood, such pathological changes as deficiency of the liver-blood or bleeding will ensue.
When the liver-blood is not adequate enough to nourish the eyes, dryness and discomfort of the eyes with blurred vision, or night blindness are likely to oc cur.
To sum up, the failure of the liver to store blood may give rise to such symptoms as menorrhagia or even metrorrhagia and metrostaxis.
Regulating the volume of circulating blood is the principal role played by the liver in distributing the blood to all parts of the body, especially to the peripheral portion of the body.
Under normal conditions, the volume of circulating blood in every part of the body remains relatively constant, but varies with the amount of activities the body engages in, and with emotional as well as climatic changes, etc.
During strenuous activity or intense excitement the liver timely releases the stored blood to the peripheral portion of the body to meet its demands, while during rest or in a calm mood, part of the circulating blood returns to the liver to be stored due to reduced amount of activities of the whole body and relatively diminished demand for the peripheral blood.
The mood is a sort of mental activities derived from the mind.
Only when the liver functions properly in storing blood, can it house the mood regularly.
If the mood is unable to be housed in the liver due to shortage of blood in the liver and deficiency of the heart-blood, such symptoms as dreaminess with liability to be frightened, insomnia with restlessness, somnanbulism, somniloquy, etc., may ensue as a result.
The tendons rely upon the liver for blood supply.
Replete liver-blood nourishes the tendons, which, in turn, make the body move actively and nimbly.
The amount of the liver-blood directly affects the property and appearance of the nails.
For example, sufficient liver-blood leads to tough and sturdy nails with ruddiness and lustrousness.
Conversely, insufficient liver-blood will result in thin and frail nails with pallor dryness and lustrelessness, and even deformed or cracked nails.
The tears come from the eyes, which are the specific body openings of the liver.
"Exhaustion of vital essence " actually embraces not only deficiency of some basic substances such as essence of life, Qi, blood, fluid of the body and their physiological hypofunction, but also physiological hypofunction and dysfunction of Zang-Fu organs, channels and collaterals, etc.
The tears perform the function of moistening and protecting the eyes. Under normal physiological conditions the lacrimal secretion just performs a moistening action inside the eyes without shedding out. Once a foreign object enters the eye, the tears are profusely secreted to clean the eyes and get rid of the foreign object.
Under pathological conditions, however, abnormal secretion of the tears may occur.
As the liver channel connects upward with the ocular connectors and vision depends on the normal flow of the liver-Qi and the nutritive function of the liver-blood, the liver is said"to, open into the eyes.
" In addition, the essence and Qi of the five Zang-organs and six Fu-organs all flow upward into the eyes, so there exist intrinsic relations between the eyes and the Zang-Fu organs.
Owing to the extremely close relation between the liver and the eyes, the former's functional state is usually reflected on the latter.
This function of the kidneys refers to the storage of vital essence in the kidneys, which provides a favorable environment in which vital essence in the body can be brought into full play, that is to say, plentiful essence is preserved without being unnecessarily eliminated so as to promote and maintain the growth, development and reproduction of the body.
As far as its source is concerned, the essence stored in the kidneys falls into two kinds: the congenital essence and acquired essence.
Because of its function of reproducing offspring it is also known as"reproductive essence." The latter, transported and transformed by the spleen and stomach, is derived from foodstuffs, and thus is also named"food essence.
" Part of the food essence is supplied for the proper functioning of the Zang-Fu organs, while its remainder is stored in the kidneys.
Although the congenital essence and acquired essence do not have a common source, they are together stored in the kidneys, depending and reacting on each other.
The congenital essence relies upon the acquired essence for a constant supply of nutrients, thereby smoothly performing its physiological functions; and the acquired essence.in turn, depends upon the congenital essence for activation of its function of production and transformation.
In the chapter Shang Gu Tian Zhen Lun of Suwen, it has been clearly pointed out that the birth, growth, full development, senility and death of a man are closely related to the vicissitudes of the kidney-essence.
As the congenital essence is being continuously nourished and replenished by the acquired essence after birth, the kidney-essence gradually becomes abundant, thereby giving rise to some physiological phenomena, such as growth of both permanent teeth and fine hairs during childhood. In the wake of wax and wane of the kidney-essence, the body goes through from childhood to puberty, then to the prime of life, and finally to old age. Throughout one's whole life, the growing conditions of the teeth, skeleton and the hairs are taken as the important signs for vicissitudes of the kidney-essence as well as for individuals of all ages.
After this, with the gradual change of abundant kidney-essence into deficient, the production of Tian Gui gradually slows down tillits utter consumption, and the reproductive power is also reduced, accordingly till its complete loss due to gradual atrophy of the sex gland. Meanwhile, the person shifts from middle age to old age.
Metabolism of body fluids is achieved through ingestion of the stomach, transportation and transformation of the spleen, the dispersing and descending functions of the lungs, and steaming and ascending actions of the kidneys with tri-Jiao as the water passage through which body fluids are transported to all parts of the body. The metabolized body fluids are converted into sweat, urine and gas to be eliminated from the body.
Steaming and as. cending actions of the kidney-Qi govern metabolism of all body fluids, because the regulation of body fluids by the spleen, lungs and other viscera relies upon the steaming and ascending actions of the kidney-Qi. This is especially ture of the formation and excretion of urine, which bear direct relation to the steaming and ascending actions of the kidney-Qi, and the formation and excretion of urine, in turn, play a most important role in the maintenance of the balance of water metabolism.
This function implies that the kidneys can receive and absorb fresh air inhaled by the lungs and make it go down to the kidneys so as to prevent shallow breathing and guarantee normal exchange of gases between the body and its environment.
Though the respiratory function of the human body is dominated by the lungs, it must rely on the receiving action of the kidneys, which is actually an embodiment of storing function of the kidneys in respiratory movement, Therefore, the kidneys' function of receiving gas must be accomplished in order that the lungs' deep breathing may occur.
For instance, if the kidneys:48 function normally, breathing would be even, moderate and harmonious.
Hypofunction of the kidneys, however, will give rise to a morbid condition marked by shallow breathing, liability to dyspnea on slight exertion, prolonged expiration and shortened inspiration.
This morbid condition is called"Failure of the kidneys in receiving gas".
Both fright and fear are attributed to the kidneys as their emotions. However, they are in general related to the heart, which controls all mental activities, and impairment of the heart-mind may bring about fear with timidness.
The bones depend for their nourishment on the marrow, which is produced from the kidney-essence, so the kidneys are said to be"in charge of the bones."The growth, development and repair of the skeleton requires the nourishment of the kidney-essence.
On the contrary, deficiency of the kidney-essence brings about the depletion of the bone marrow, giving rise to dysostosis, infantile metopism and debility of bones.
Owing to the progressive decline of the old people's kidney-Qi and hence inability of the bones to obtain adequate nourishment of the bone marrow, they must show osteoporosis, liability to fracture and difficulty in reduction after fracture as well.
Teeth as the remainder of the bone are nourished by the kidney-essence.
When the kidney-essence is replete, the teeth would be solid and unlikely to shed.
The growth of the hairs completely relies on the supply of the essence and blood.
The kidneys store the essence, so their condition may be reflected on the hairs.
Since blood has the function of nourishing the hairs, the latter are called"the remainder of blood.
"Generally speaking, premature senility, dry and withered hairs and premature greying or loss of hairs are all related to insufficiency of the kidney-essence or deficiency of blood.
It is transformed from the kidney-essence and then swallowed instead of being spit out. It has the function of moisturizing the kidney-essence.
So a great deal of spitting or long-standing spitting easily impairs the kidney-essence.
In addition, spittle also bears some relation to the spleen and stomach.
For instance, repletion of the kidney-essence brings about plenitude of the marrow and fullness of the brain, and sharp and quick hearing follows as a result.
The excretion of urine is related to the function of the urinary bladder, but depends on the functioning of the kidney-Qi for its accomplishment.
Therefore, frequent micturition, enuresis, oliguria or anuresis are all related to dysfunction of the kidney-Qi.
It pointed out:"The gate of life is the eye."However, Nan Jing claimed that "There are two kidneys in a human body, the left one being the kidney proper and the right the gate of life.
The gate of life is the house of essence and mind and also the lodgement of primordial Qi. It is thus the viscus where man's semen is stored or woman's uterus is linked up". Since then, this thesis had attracted considerable attentionof physicians in later ages who advanced various opinions on the location and physiological functions of the gate of life.
Attached to the liver and located in between the hepatic lobes, the gallbladder is the first of the six Fu-organs. It is exterior-interiorly related to the liver because of the interconnection between their channels.
The gallbladder is one of the extraordinary Fu-organs as well as of the six Fu-organs, because like the Fu-organs, it excretes bile to help digest foodstuff, but unlike such ordinary Fu-organs as the stomach and the intestines, it doesn't receive and transport food and water.
Instead, it stores"refined juice" (bile). In this sense, it is described as belonging to the extraordinary Fu-organs.
This denotes that the gallbladder stores a clear and pure fluid, or bile, which being bitter in taste and yellow-green in colour, derives from the essence-Qi of the liver, converges into the gallbladder, and is excreted to the small intestine to help digestion. This functional activity of the gallbladder is an important basis for normal functioning of the spleen and stomach in transporting-transforming foodstuff.
The main function of the gallbladder is to store and excrete bile, whose production and excretion are controlled and regulated by the liver's function in governing normal flow of Qi. Consequently, if the liver functions properly, the gallbladder will excrete bile regularly and freely, and the spleen and stomach will also conduct the transportation and transformation functional activities normally. When depression of the liver-Qi leads to the obstruction of excretion of bile, there may appear distending pain in the hypochondriac region, poor appetite, abdominal distension. loose stool, etc.
The upper part of the gastric cavity refers mainly to the cardia, its middle part to the body of stomach, and its lower part to the pylorus.
The main function of the stomach is to receive and decompose foodstuff and the functional feature of the stomach-Qi is descending.
The stomach is exterior-interiorly related to the spleen due to interconnection between their channels.
This is how the stomach functions to receive and decompose foodstuff.
This function of the stomach is of great importance in maintaining the body's life activities and enhancing its resistance against disease.
As mentioned in the chapter Ping Ren Qi Xiang Lun ofSuwen,"Man depends for survival on food and water, without which man cannot live long."
Generally speaking, the oollateral venules only visible at Fengguan indicate that the pathogens invade collaterals and the disease is mild; when the: collateral venules dark in colour extending from Fengguan to Qiguan denote an invasion of channels by pathogens, a serious disease ensues. If the collateral venules are visible at Mingguan that implies that the pothogens go into Zang-Fu organs and the condition is dangerous; if the collateral venules directly reach the tip of the index finger, known as "Superficial venule visible from guan to the nail of index Finger", that indicates a critical stage of disease most probably followed by an unfavourable prognosis.
The decomposed food mass in the stomach must move down to the small intestine to be further digested and absorbed. In this sense, sending foodstuff downward is a normal functional activity of the stomach.
According to the viscera-phase doctrine, the descending function.of the stomach, along with the ascending function of the spleen, is used to denote the functions of the whole digestive system of the body. In fact, the descending function of the stomach includes the activity of the small intestine to transfer the residues of food to the large intestine and that of the large intestine to turn the wastes into feces to be excreted out of the body.
In a narrow sense, it refers only to the physiological functions of the stomach, particularly those of receiving and decomposing foodstuff. In a broad sense, however, it signifies the common physiological functions of both the spleen and stomach in receiving, digesting, transporting and transforming foodstuff.
Since the spleen and stomach are the source for the production of Qi-blood, the vicissitudes of Qi-blood of the body can be reflected-in the pulse condition. Therefore, the moderate and smooth pulse is referred to as"pulse with the stomach-Qi".
The main physiological functions of the small intestine are to temporarily store and further digest the preliminarily digested food, and to separate the useful substances from the waste ones.
Firstly, it denotes that the small intestine receives the preliminarily digested food from the stomach. Secondly, it indicates that the food received in the small intestine temporarily remains there for a certain time in order to be further digested and absorbed.
Hence, a passage from chapter Ling Lan Mi Dian Lun ofSuwen says:"The small intestine is an organ for receiving foodstuffs where they are further digested.
Firstly, the small intestine separates the digested foodstuff into two parts, the refined nutritious substances and the residues of the food. Secondly, it absorbs the refined nutritious substances and transfers downward the residues of the food to the large intestine. Thirdly, it also absorbs a considerable amount of fluid while absorbing the refined nutritious substances.
As a result of its ability to absorb fluid, the small intestine functions properly in separating the refined nutritious substances from the waste ones, thereby promoting regular urination and defecation. However, if the small intestine does not function well in this respect, loose stool and oliguria may result. This is known as"Small intestine diarrhea", which is often treated by diuresis to dry the feces.
As this function of the small intestine is quite important in the process of forming the refined nutritious substances from food, it also furnishes an essential basis for the functioning of the spleen in sending up essential substances.
The main function of the large intestine is to convey and transform waste products.
It is exterior-interiorly related with the lungs due to the interconnection between their channels.
The large intestine receives food residues sent down from the small intestine and, in the process of conveying them, absorbs a part of the surplus fluid and then turns them into feces to be eliminated from the body by the anus. Thus, it is stated in the chapter Ling Lan Mi Dian Lun of the bookSuwen says:"The large intestine is an organ for conveyance accompanied by formation of feces.
It communicates directly with the kidneys, to which it is exterior-interiorly related due to the interconnection between their channels.
The main function of the urinary bladder in storing and discharging urine is accomplished through the functioning of the kidney-Qi.
Urine is formed from body fluids through the action of the kidney-Qi and then sent down to the urinary bladder, where it is retained to a certain amount, and automatically discharged from the body in time.
These morbid conditions are mostly related to the dysfunction of the kidney-Qi.
Primordial Qi, the most essential Qi of the body, must replenish the whole body through tri-Jiao. Therefore, a passage from the book, NanJing says:"Tri-Jiao is the thoroughfare of primordial Qi where the Qi of the three portions of the body passes through the five Zang and six Fu-organs.
"To sum up, it is a passageway for ascending-descending and entering-exiting of Qi, which is actually distributed to five Zang and six Fu-organs and further to all parts of the body through Tri-Jiao.
The chapter Ling Lan Mi Dian says:"Tri-Jiao is an organ in charge of water circulation where body fluids flow smoothly.
"It is thus clear that Tri-Jiao performs the function of dredging water passages, thereby serving as the pathway for lifting-lowering and entering-exiting of body fluids.
Water metabolism is accomplished through the coordination of many viscera such as the lungs, spleen, stomach, intestines, kidneys and urinary bladder, with Tri-Jiao as its passageway so that body fluids can ascend-descend and enter-exit normally.
Its physiological function is to distribute the vital essence throughout the body. As pointed out in the chapter Ying Wei Sheng Hui of Lingshu:"The upper-Jiao resembles a sprayer".
That is to say, the upper-Jiao is responsible for upward dispersion and outward spread of the nutrients, and its functional state is compared to the natural fog-dew which permeates throughout the earth to nourish all things.
Its physiological, function is to excrete food residues and urine.
By"the lower-Jiao resembling water passages" is meant that its excretory function is similar to the drainage system in a city.
In the meantime, the spirit, consciousness and thinking of the human body are connected with the five Zang-organs. For instance, the heart houses spirit and is in charge of joy, the liver houses mood and is in charge of anger; the spleen houses idea and is in charge of anxiety; the lungs house soul and are in charge of sorrow; and the kidneys house will and are in charge of fear.
It is also said in the chapter Kou Wen of the same book that"Insufficiency of vital essence of the head leads to the empty feeling in the brain, tinnitus, hung head with debility and vertigo".
The spinal cord upward connects with the brain which is formed by the convergence of marrow.
In case of exuberance of the kidney-essence the"reservoir of marrow" is replenished, the brain is well developed, and the head can fully fulfil its function as"house of intelligence. " Conversely, in case of deficiency of the kidney-es. sence the"reservoir of marrow"fails to be nourished, hence re. sulting in a series of pathological changes. A passage from the chapter Ling Lan Mi Dian says:"The kidneys are responsible for staunchness of the body and intelligence of a person".
In fact, this is the concrete manifestation of the funcion of the kidneys in dominating the bones and producing the marrow.
Chong channel and Ren channel both originate from the uterus. In addition, the heart governs blood circulation, the liver stores blood and the spleen keeps the blood flowing within the vessels, serving as the source of Qi-blood. All of them are closely related to the uterus in physiological functions and pathological changes.
The channels of the heart and the small intestine are interrelated to each other, so"The heart and the small intestine are said to be interior-exteriorly related".
Therefore,"The lungs and the large intestine are said to be interior-exteriorly related". The purifying and descending functions of the lung-Qi help the large intestine to perform its transporting function, and proper functioning of the large intestine, in turn, aids the lung-Qi in fulfilling its purifying and descending functions.
Pathologically, the lungs and the large intestine can affect each other.
For example, the impairment of purifying and descending functions of the lungs may give rise to difficulty in defecation and, conversely, the stagnation of large intestine-Qi can impede the purifying and descending functions of the lung-Qi.
It is suitable for the spleen to send up but for the stomach to send down.
Pathologically, hypofunction of the spleen due to dampness leads to failure to vigorously transport and elevate, thus impairing the functions of the stomach in receiving and lowering, and there may appear poor appetite, nausea, epigastric distension, etc. On the contrary, the retention of food in the stomach due to intemperance of food intake brings about dysfunction of the stomach-Qi in descending and that of the spleen in elevating and transporting, and such symptoms as abdominal distension, diarrhea and others are likely to occur.
The channels of the liver and the gallbladder are interrelated to each other, so these two organs are said to be interior-exteriorly related".
If this function of the liver is abnormal, the secretion and excretion of bile would be harmfully affected. Conversely, obstructed excretion of bile may also impair the function of the liver in controlling normal flow of Qi.
Besides, the liver and the gallbladder are also closely involved in mental activity, because the liver is in charge of deliberation and the galbladder, in charge of judgement. The matter after deep deliberation needs to be judged and the judgement to be formed, in turn, must be based on the deliberation.
The functions of the urinary bladder in storing and excreting urine depend on the functioning of the kidney-Qi.
In case of sufficiency of the kidney-Qi, the kidneys fulfil their reserving function normally and the urinary bladder functions to open and close at the right moment.
This relationship between the heart and the lungs is brought about through the functional activities of pectoral Qi in linking up the heart and the lungs and in promoting breathing. Thus, the coordination and balance between blood circulation and respiration can be enhanced.
In addition, convergence of vessels in the lungs can aid the heart in maintaining blood circulation. Therefore their relationship can be briefly summarized in the following quotation:"Qi being the commander of blood".
As to pathological interaffection, dysfunction of the lungs may lead to abnormal flow or retardation of blood, manifested as oppressive sensation in chest, changes in rate or rhythm of the heart, or even bluish purple lips, as well as purplish tongue due to blood stasis.
In the first aspect, normal function of the spleen in transport makes the growth exuberant and blood replete, hence furnishing adequate blood supply for the heart.
In the second aspect, vigorous spleen-Qi guarantees normal function of the spleen in controlling blood flow within the vessels instead of escaping from them. Pathologically, the heart and the spleen often influence each other.
For instance, excessive thinking gives rise both to internal consumption of the heart-blood and to impairment of function of the spleen in transport.
All the above pathological changes result in a morbid condition known as"deficiency of Qi and blood in the heart and spleen", marked by palpitation, Insomnia, dreaminess, anorexia, lassitude, sallow complexion, etc.
As the heart governs blood and the liver stores it, their relationship may be viewed from two aspects:(1) blood circulation and (2) mental activities. Firstly, only when normal functioning of the heart brings about normal blood circulation, can the liver store what it should store.
Secondly, the heart controls mental activities and the liver adjusts emotional activities. Therefore, spirit, consciousness, thinking and emotions are controlled by the heart, but they are closely related to the liver's dredging function.
The heart corresponding to fire is situated in the.upper part of the body, while the kidneys corresponding to water in the lower.
The heart-fire needs to go down to the kidneys while the kidney-water needs to go up to the heart.
Therefore, their functional conditions are concerned with the vicissitudes of vital Qi.
In the latter case, the functions of the lungs in dispersing, descending and maintaining unobstructed water passages are beneficial to the transporting-transforming function of the spleen, while the physiological activities of the spleen in transporting nutrients and fluids to the lungs not only are the prerequisite for the lungs'function in clearing and regulating water passages, but also provide the lungs with necessary nutrients.
The protracted lung-disease can also affect the spleen-Qi, accompanied by abdominal distension, poor appetite, loose stool and so on.
The relationship between the lungs and the liver is mainly reflected in the regulation of functional activities of Qi.
Since the lungs tend downwards and the liver tends upwards, both of which are an important link in the regulation of functional activities of Qi.
For instance, excessive ascent of the liver or deficient descent of the lungs may lead mostly to cough with dyspnea, or even hemoptysis, a syndrome known as"the lungs attacked by excessive liver-fire".
On the other hand, impairment of the lungs'purifying and descending function together with overabundance of inner dryness-heat may also affect the liver, resulting in stagnation of the liver-Qi, manifested as cramping pain and distension in the chest and hypochondrium, dizziness, headache, flushed face, with congested eyes, etc, at the time of cough.
Either insuffieiency of the kidney-essence or deficiency of the lungs with kidneys involved can bring about failure of the kidneys to receive air, marked by dyspnea on slight exertion, and so on.
The liver stores blood and governs normal flow of Qi, while the spleen controls blood flow and dominates transportation and transformation, serving as the source of generating Qi-biood.
Therefore, their relation is chiefly one between the normal flow of Qi and the transporting-transforming function. That is to say, the transporting-transforming function of the spleen is dependent on the dredging function of the liver, whose normal functioning, in turn, aids the spleen in transport.
Conversely, dysfunction of the spleen in transport may bring about the retention of damp-heat in the interior and further interfere with the function of the liver to maintain the unrestrained flow of Qi and with the excretion of bile, giving rise to jaundice.
For instance, when the spleen functions well in transport, and the blood in abundance doesn't extravasate, the liver has enough blood to store, otherwise deficiency of the liver-blood is likely to occur.
Pathologically, they can affect each other, thus resulting in deficiency of both essence and blood.
Besides, both of them house the ministerial fire, hyperactivity of which requires appropriate treatment for both organs.
On the other hand, the essence stored in the kidneys relies also on the replenishment of Qi-blood transformed from foodstuff.
Pathologically, the spleen and the kidneys or acquired essence and congenital essence influence each other, and act on each other as cause or effect alternately.
The physiological functions of Qi include impulsing, warming, defending, communicating and regulating, etc.
For this reason, Zhang Jingyue said:"The life of a human being relies totally upon Qi".
Among them the transporting-transforming function of the spleen and stomach is particularly important, for man after birth must depend on the spleen and stomach for absorption of nourishment from foodstuff so as to maintain life activities; meanwhile, the congenital essenc-Qi also relies on essential substances from foodstuff for replenishment.
Only through the warming action of Qi can the body's temperature be kept constant, can all Zang-Fu organs, channels and collaterals and other structures perform their respective physiological functions, and can such liquid substances as blood and body fluids carry on regular circulation. As the saying goes:"blood flows in warm circumstances but coagulates in cold".
This function refers chiefly to the action of Qi in reserving Liquid substances, such as blood and body fluids. i, e., keeping the blood flowing within the vessels so as to prevent its extravasation, controlling the amount of the secretion and excretion of sweat, urine, saliva, stomach-fluid, intestine-fluid, semen, etc, to prevent their wasteful consumption.
It is the primary motive force for life activities of the human body and also the most essential substance for maintaining vital functions.
It is formed by the kidney-essence but depends on food essence transported by the spleen and stomach for nourishment and replenishment, It flows throughout the body via Tri-Jiao, as is stated inClassic on Medical Problems problem 66;"Tri-Jiao is the passage-way for the primordialQi".
The pectoral Qi performs two main functions:(1) It acts on the respiratory tract to complete breathing process and its vicissitudes bear relation to the strength of speech, voice and respiration.
(2) It runs through the vessels into the heart so as to keep Qi-blood circulating.
Therefore, the flow of Qi-blood, the temperature and motility of the trunk and limbs, the perceptibility of visual and aural sensations, the strength and rhythm of the heart beat and so on, are all related to the vicissitudes of the pectoral Qi.
Since it accumulates in the thorax (also called Tan Zhong). the position of Xuli (corresponding to the location where cardiac apex beats) is usually used to detect the vicissitudes of the pectoral Qi.
As the spleen is in charge of sending up and the stomach of sending down, both of them are the centre of ascending-descending and exiting-entering movements of Qi of the body.
The ascending function of the spleen enables some internal organs of the body to keep themselves at their respective positions. Thus, sinking of Qi of the middle-Jiao may result in lassitude, loose stools, or protracted diarrhea with prolapse of rectum, even prolapse of internal organs.
The nutritive Qi, as its name implies, is highly rich in nourishment and is mainly formed by the pure and pliable parts of the food essence transported by the spleen and stomach.
It has two physiological functions:(1) It nourishes the whole body, and (2) It is transformed into blood. In other words, the finest parts of essential substances from the foodstuff constitute the major components of the nourishing Qi which are nutrients necessary for the Zang-Fu organs, channels and collaterals, etc, to carry on their physiological activities.
Its physiological functions may be considered in three aspects:(1) It protects the body surface against exogenous pathogens;(2) It warms and nourishes the Zang-Fu organs, muscles, skin with hairs, and so on;(3) It regulates and controls the opening-closing of pores for the discharge of sweat so as to maintain a relatively constant body temperature.
The defensive Qi is so named because of its protective action.
Though the movements forms of Qi are varied in form they can be summarized in four basic forms as follows: ascending, descending, out-going and in-going.
Blood circulates ceaselessly through the vessels, by which it is carried to the Zang-Fu organs internally and to the skin, muscles, tendons and bones externally, to exert fully nourishing and moisturizing effects on all the organs and tissues of the body, thereby maintaining its normal physiological activities.
This is a brief summary of the nourishing and moisturizing effects of the blood.
For this reason, it is stated in the book Suwen:"The blood is regarded as the material base of vitality of the human body and has to be nursed with caution.
The dispersing-descending action of the lungs and convergence of vessels in the lungs as well as the control of normal flow of Qi by the liver are important factors contributing to the circulation of blood. On the other hand, the function of the spleen in keeping blood flowing within the vessels and that of the liver in storing blood are also the important fac tors governing blood circulation.
As the blood flows within the vessels, they are known as "The house of blood".
The body fluid is a general term for all normal liquid components of the body, including the inner fluids existing in various organs and tissues and their normal secretions, such as the gastric juice, intestinal juice, saliva and tears, etc, Like Qi and blood, the body fluid is also a kind of essential substance constituting the human body and contributing to the maintenance of its life activities.
For instance, when distributed in the body surface, it moistens the muscles and skin with hairs, when permeating through the body orifices, it moistens and protects eyes, nose, mouth and other openings; when infiltrating into the vessels, it nourishes and smooths the vessels as the basic component of blood; when pouring into the internal organs, it nourishes and moistens them and when seeping into the joint cavities, marrow cavities and the skull, it lubricates the joints, nourishes and moistens the bone marrow, spinal cord and brain.
By the production of blood is meant that the formation of blood relies on the functional activities of Qi.
By the propelling of blood we mean that Qi is the motive force for blood flow.
Under pathological conditions, blood and body fluid usually influence each other. Therefore, for patients with excessive bleeding the practice of diaphoresis is not indicated. On the other hand, for patients with deficient body fluid due to profuse sweating the treatment by removing blood stasis with drastic drugs is not indicated, either.
The meridian system acts as specific passageways for the circulation of Qi and blood throughout the body, the interconnection between visceral organs and extremities, and the communication of the upper with the lower and of the interior with the exterior.
This system links the Zang-Fu organs internally and joins the tendons, muscles and skin externally.
The channels may be classified into two categories: regular channels and extra channels.
Moreover, the branches of the twelve regular channels can strengthen the links between every two exterior-interiorly related regular channels and complement the inadequate aspects of the regular channels due to the capability of these branches to reach all the organs and bodily areas that the regular channels can't reach.
The collaterals which are the minor branches of the channels are classified into three groups: major, superficial, and minute.
They are the muscular system and the body surface respectively which are distributed along the routes of the twelve regular channels.
Unlike the twelve regular channels, they are not regularly distributed, nor are they directly connected with Zang-Fu organs. They are not exterior-interiorly related to each other, either.
That is why they are named"eight extra channels", as distinct from the twelve regular ones.
They perform the following three functions: firstly, they further streng then the close relations between the twelve regular channels; secondly, they regulate Qi-blood in the channels; and thirdly, they constitute the physiological and pathological media for connections between some Zang-organs, such as the liver and kidneys, and the extraordinary Fu-organs, such as the uterus, brain and spinal cord.
The branches of the twelve regular channels originate respectively from the elbows and knees of the limbs where just the twelve regular channels pass through. The three physiological functions they perform are as follows. Firstly, they strengthen the inner connexion between each pair of the exterior-interiorly related channels: secondly, they promote the inner relation of the body proper because of their dominant action on the collaterals; and lastly, they convey Qi-blood to nourish the whole body.
The twelve regular channels and their associated collaterals are fixedly distributed over the body surface, and accordingly, the skin of the whole body is also divided into twelve parts, known as the twelve skin areas.
These skin areas are the site where Qi of the twelve regular channels disperses. They are of some help in the treatment as well as diagnosis of disease. For instance, observing the morphological changes and discoloration on different skin areas helps to diagnose some disorders of Zang-Fu organs and meridians.
Living in nature, man is always affected by variations in weather and environmental factors.
The science dealing with the nature, characteristics and laws of various kinds of pathogenic factors and clinical manifestations of the disease they produce is called etiology.
The etiology of traditional Chinese medicine reveals the cause of a disease not merely by means of visual observation, but most important, traces it by analysis of symptoms and signs on the basis of clinical manifestations of the disease.
The introduction of"the theory of the three categories of etiologic factors", though far from perfect, gave an enormous impetus to the research into the etiology in later ages.
Under normal circumstances such six different climatic conditions as wind, cold, summer-heat, dampness, dryness and fire are spoken of as Liu Qi, which are prerequisite for the growth of all things on earth and therefore, do no harm to the human body.
Consequently, they are the exogenous pathogenic factors brought about by the changes of the six kinds of natural factors and wide variations in bodily constitution.
For instance, diseases due to pathogenic wind occur more frequently in spring, and summerheat disorders in summer. One is more likely to suffer from arthritis when he lives long in a damp place and suffer from diseases due to dryness-heat and pathogenic fire when he works in hot environment.
(2) Each of the six exogenous pathogenic factors can cause disease alone or more than two can do so simultaneously, e.g.,"wind, cold and dampness combined as a pathogen causing stagnation-syndrome of Qi and blood", common cold of wind-cold type, and damp-heat diarrhea, etc.
(3) They can not only interact on one another in the course of the occurrence of a disease, but can also transform themselves into one another in given conditions and the nature of its pathogensis and syndromes change accordingly.
(4) They cause disease through the following channels: by way of superficial muscles or through the mouth and nose or by way of both at the same time.
(2) Wind pathogens are characterized by constant movement and rapid change.
By constant movement is meant that pathogenic wind tends to move constantly, causing diseases marked by migratory pain in the part involved.
As for rapid change, it implies that pathogenic wind tends to change rapidly and frequently, causing diseases characterized by abrupt onset and variable changes.
For example, urticaria is marked by migratory itches of skin and their alternate appearance.
This is what is termed "German measles" in traditional Chinese medicine. (3) Wind-pathogen is the predominant pathogenic factor.
As the first one of the six exogenic pathogenic agents, wind-pathogen is the predisposing factor contributing to exopathic diseases while all the other pathogenic factors, such as cold-pathogen, damp-pathogen, dry-pathogen, usually invade the human body in association with wind pathogen.
(2) Stagnation of cold nature; invasion by pathogenic cold brings about retardation of circulation of Qi and blood in the body and block of channels and collaterals, from which pain results.
(3) Contraction due to cold means that attack of pathogenic cold results in disturbance of visceral function, closure of sweat pores and contraction of muscles manifested by anhidrosis, spasm of muscles, etc.
(2) Upward flow and dispersion of summer-heat pathogens lead to consumption of Qi and body fluid.
Invasion of summer-heat pathogens often causes excessive sweating due to the opening of sweat pores, which, in turn, leads to consumption of more body fluid and Qi, often accompanied by some Qi-deficiency symptoms, such as shortness of breath, and lassitude.
(3) Summer-heat pathogens often invade the body in combination with dampness.
As in summer it is rainy and therefore damp, pathogenic summer-heat invades the body together with pathogenic dampness, clinically marked by some summer-heat symptoms and by some dampness ones as well, such as lassitude in the limbs, stuffy sensation in the chest, nausea, vomiting, etc.
Dampness in excess, causing disease, is said to be pathogenic dampness.
(2) Dampness is characterized by heaviness and turbidity.
Dampness is a pathogenic factor, substantial, heavy and turbid in nature. Its invasion of the body often gives rise to such symptoms as heaviness in the head as if it were tightly bound, numbness and heaviness in the joints as well as turbid excretions and secretions.
For example, the syndrome of arthritis manifested by fixed pain, numbness and heaviness in the limbs and joints involved, is generally known as "damp anthralgia".
Such symptoms as excessive secretions in the eyes, dirty complexion, pus-bloody stool, turbid urine and massive leukorrhea, eczema and stranguria with turbid urine are characteristic of diseases due to invasion of damp pathogen.
Since the lungs as one of the delicate Zang-organs, prefer purity and moistness rather than dryness and communicate with the external atmosphere, dry pathogens, entering the body through the mouth and nose, tend to impair the lungs.
The impairment of the lungs and consumption of body fluid by dry pathogen result in impairment of dispersing, purifying and descending functions of the lungs, marked by such symptoms as dry cough, sticky phlegm difficult to be coughed up, phlegm with blood, and gasping pain in the chest.
That is to say, the symptoms caused by fire tend to appear in the upper portion of the body.
For example, the flaring-up. of the heart-fire shows fire symptoms of the Heart Channel marked by oral ulceration, and that of the liver-fire presents such symptoms as conjunctival congestion with painful swelling, and mental disturbance due to flaring-up fire pathogen flaring-up fire pathogen accompanied by coma, delirium, etc.
(2) Fire-pathogen is apt to consume Qi and body fluid.
(3) Fire-pathogen is liable to stir up wind and disturb blood circulation.
Furthermore, fire-pathogen may speed up blood flow, burn the channels and collaterals or even cause extravasation of blood, thereby bringing about various types of hemorrhage.
Following are some special features of epidemic pathogenic factor:(1) It is obviously infectious and epidemic.
Epidemic pathogens, are spread through the air or by contact and enter the body by wáy of the mouth and nose.
Once infected, "one will infect other persons susceptible to the infection", and the epidemic disease will prevail rapidly in the community, thus leading to its onset among large population.
The factors contributing to this disturbance are numerous, but it results mainly from dysfunction of the lungs, spleen, and liver, and obstruction of Tri-Jiao as passageway. Of these factors, the most important one is dysfunction of the spleen in transportation and transformation as the saying goes, "Such syndromes as dampness, swelling and distention are all attributable to dysfunction of the spleen." By disturbance in discharge of body fluid is meant edema resulting from water retention due to weakened function of internal organs to transform fluid into sweat and urine.
According to traditional Chinese medicine, seven emotions refer to the seven emotional manifestations, namely, joy, anger, melancholy, meditation, grief, fear and terror. They are emotional responses of the body to environmental stimuli since they are, in fact, normal mental activities. They cause no disease under normal conditions.
Briefly speaking, emotional activities originate from Qi and blood in five Zang-organs, but emotional stress can also impair their Qi and blood.
For instance, anger is seen when the liver's function in controlling normal flow of Qi is impaired.
On the other hand, emotional stress, acting on the relevant Zang- organ, causes its dysfunction, disorder of Qi and irregular flow of blood.
For example, rage impairs the liver, causing adverse and upward flow of Qi and blood, and, therefore, such symptom as hematemesis, or even syncope in serious case, is likely to occur.
Unlike the six exogenic pathogenic factors, which invade the body through the mouth, nose and skin pores, seven emotions cause disease by directly acting on corresponding internal organs.
The heart, as the commanding one of Zang-Fu organs, houses the mind. The impairment of emotions will first affect the heart-Qi and then other organs.
For example, excessive anxiety may cause retention of the heart-Qi and give rise to accumulation of the spleen-Qi.
(2) They affect the functional activities of Zang-Fu organs.
For example, anger injures the liver, and rage causes adverse or smooth flow of the liver-Qi; joy impairs the heart, and excessive joy tends to cause unsteadiness of the heart-Qi and mental derangement; anxiety impairs the spleen, and excessive anxiety leads to accummulation of the spleen-Qi and anorexia; fear impairs the kidneys and lungs, and excessive fear gives rise to unconsolidation of the kidney-Qi and incontinence of urine and stool; melancholy injures the lungs and excessive melancholy leads to insufficiency of the lung-Qi, shortness of breath and weakness of muscles; terror impairs the heart, and excessive terror brings about dysfunction of the heart-Qi, utter stupefaction of all the six vital organs and flusteration.
For example, dysfunction of Zang-Fu organs in digesting and transporting nutrients due to insufficiency of Qi and blood may produce symptoms similar to excess syndrome, such as abdominal fullness, distension and pain, taut pulse, etc.
In the course of a disease, any fluctuation in a patient's emotion often aggravates his condition or even abruptly deteriorates it.
Prolonged scantysupply of food results in malnutrition and insufficiency of Qi and blood with a resultant disease.
On the other hand, excessive nourishment intake due to overeating, which exceeds the transporting and transforming capabilities of the spleen and stomach, also causes disease, marked by such symptoms as indigestion, epigastric distention, eructation with fetid odor and nausea, anorexia, vomiting, diarrhea.
As the chapter Bi Lun of Suwen says, "Overeating tends to impair the gastrointestinal organs."Intake of insanitary food may also cause many different gastrointestinal 110. diseases or parasitic ones, manifested by abdominal pain, vomiting, diarrhea etc.
Intake of stale food or food containing poison usually brings about such poisoning symptoms as severe abdominal pain, vomiting and diarrhea, or even coma or death in severe cases.
Again, overwork can be classified into three types: undue physical exertion, undue mental exertion, and intemperance in sexual life.
Undue physical exertion refers to constant overwork from which one breaks down and results in impairment and exhaustion of Qi, as is stated in the chapter Ju Tong Lun of Suwen:"Exhaustion of Qi is due to strenuous labour".
Too much mental work and meditation consume the heart-blood and impair the spleen-Qi, thereby producing such symptoms as paipitation due to denutrition of the heart, insomnia, amnesia and anorexia and abdominal distention due to stagnation of the spleen-Qi.
This is a syndrome of insufficiency of the lung-Qi and the kidney-Qi.
That is why the chapter Xuan Ming Wu Qi Pian of Suwen says,"Prolonged bed rest injures Qi".
This function may be summarized as follows: the lungs make rhythmic breathing movements, regulate the functioning of Qi of the whole body, assist the heart in promoting blood circulation, and help maintain the normal flow, distribution and discharge of body fluids.
And the latter is often seen on the hand, feet, auricullae, etc. At the very start, the affected areas fail to be warmed and nourished by Qi and blood which are obstructed by pathogenic cold. Its clinical manifestations are local pale skin and cold numbness, followed by swelling and itching pain and scorching heat or blisters of various size.
The phlegm-retention is a combined term for phlegm as well as fluid-retention, with the dense, viscid and thicker dampness called phlegm and the thinner one named fluid-retention.
Phlegm retention is further subdivided into tangible and formless. The former is a kind of mucoid substance visible, palpable or vocal and the latter, an invisible fluid stagnating in Zang-Fu and channel tissues but presents clinical manifestations, according to which it can be determined and cured with an expectorant.
For instance, the spleen governs transportation and transformation of water and fluid, as the saying goes:"Essence is sent upward to the lungs by the spleen-Qi". The lungs perform dispersing, purifying and descending functions, regulate water passages and promote diffusion of body fluid.
And the kidneys dominate water metabolism, in which clean fluid is retained and turbid fluid flows down into the urinary bladder to form urine for excretion.
Accumulated in the heart, it causes obstruction of circulation of the heart blood, accompanied by such symptoms as choking sensation in the chest, palpitation, etc.
(2) It prevents the Qi from ascending or descending, and entering or exiting.
For example, stagnation of phlegm in the lungs may interfere with their dispersing and descending functions, accompanied by dyspnea or cough, whereas that in the stomach may cause the failure of descending of the stomach-Qi, manifested by such symptoms as serious vomiting, fullness in the stomach, etc.
(3) It affects water metabolism.
Phlegm is formed by disturbance in water metabolism. Once stagnated, it can interfere with Qi in the performance of its ascending and descending functions.
Stagnation of phlegm retention in the heart may block the heart orifice and bring about impairment of mental activities, marked by such symptoms as coma and dementia.
What is more, manic-depressive psychosis may also occur as a result of mental disturbance due to phlegm-fire.
Its formation may exert a further influence upon the circulation of Qi and blood, thereby bringing about dysfunction of Zang-Fu tissues and some new pathological changes, accompanied by a variety of symptoms. Consequently, it is aiso considered as a pathogenic factor.
It can be formed either by accumulation of stagnant blood in certain spots due to impeded circulation of blood or by inability of blood to be dispersed or eliminated due to internal bleeding as a result of traumatic injury and other factors.
It may result from the impairment of emotions, accumulation of the liver-Qi, and disturbance in functional activities of Qi.
Impeded circulation of blood due to stagnation of Qi leads to blood stasis.
(2) Deficiency of Qi. Deficiency of Qi, the commander of blood, leads to slow transportation and sluggish flow of blood or to loss of control of flow of extravasated blood from the vessels into the tissues without being timely dispersed, thereby resulting in blood stasis. (3) Blood-cold.
(5) Bleeding due to traumatic injury.
Contusions, sprains squeezing, pressing, etc can externally injure muscles and internally impair Zang-Fu organs, breaking blood vessels with blood escaping from them and making extravasated blood retained in Zang-Fu organs and tissues without being timely eliminated or dispersed. And blood stasis occurs as a result. (6) Improper diet.
Its main pathological characteristics can be summed up as follows:(1) Pain.
That is what is known as"no removal of stagnated blood, no hemostasis."(4) Cyanosis.
These assume the form of purplish spots on the skin or the tongue accompanied by thready but deep thready, hesitant and taut pulse.
In addition, prolonged stagnation of blood may be accompanied by such symptoms as darkish complexion, squamous and dry skin (scaly with a rough sensation). As the saying goes:"If the stagnated blood is not removed, no new blood is formed.
"Also, mental disturbance due to blood stasis may produce some mental symptoms; such as mania, coma, etc.
As has been commonly said, "sufficient vital Qi inside the body can prevent invasion by pathogens".
However, when vital Qi is not sufficient enough to resist the invasion of pathogens, that is, when the body resistance is lowered, they manage to enter the body and cause disease. It has also been commonly said that"Intrusion of pathogens certainly results from insufficiency of vital Qi."
So pathogens are said to be the predominant factor in the causation of disease.
A disease may occur if pathogens are too exuberant for vital Qi to overcome because its resistance is rather limited.
When pathogens invade the body, vital Qi immediately rushes to the site of invasion to fight them off.
If vital Qi is powerful enough to guard against invasion, it's very hard for pathogens to get into the body, or even though they do enter the body, the invaders are likely to be repelled without causing any trouble.
In general, slight invasion by pathogens leads to mild disorders while serious invasion by pathogens, to severe ones. Moreover, diseases vary with the locations or parts affected.
For exmaple, attack of the skin by pathogens generally presents exterior syndromes whereas invasion of the Zang-Fu organs produces interior ones.
External environment refers mainly to living and working surroundings, including climatic variations, geographical features, environmentalsanitation, etc.
However, abnormal changes in weather or poilution of living and working surroundings predispose man to disease.
The strength of vital Qi is closely linked with the constitutional and mental state of the body.
For instance, a strong and vigorous constitution (euthesia) is a manifestation of sufficient vital Qi while a weak or feeble constitution, a manifestation of deficient vital Qi.
In addition, mental state is directly affected by emotional factors.
Joyful emotions and mental happiness bring about balance between Qi and blood, coordination between functions of Zang-Fu organs and exuberance of vital Qi.
Therefore, a sturdy constitution and happy emotions are usually accompanied by exuberance of vital Qi and strong resistance to disease. Consequently, it's dificult for pathogens to invade the body. Even if they manage to do so, the diseaee they produce can be easily warded off.
Conversely, a weak physique and emotional depression will bring about decreased vital Qi and weakened resistance, both of which, in turn, make possible occurrence of disease due to invasion by pathogens and often aggravate it once it occurs.
It denotes the mechanism of occurrence, development and change of a disease, all of which are closely related to the strength of yital Qi and nature of pathogenic factors.
On invasion by pathogens, vital Qi of the body rises up against them, and a struggle is going on between vital Qi and pathogens.
This is what is meant by"Differentiation between the sthenia nature and the asthenia-nature according to wax or wane of pathogens and vital Qi".
Therefore, the process of many diseases in a certain sense is that of a struggle between vital Qi and pathogens ahd that of the vicissitudes they undergo, which is said: to be one of the pathogeneses.
"By syndrome of excess nature is meant mainly exuberance of pathogens, or a pathological reaction with excessive pathogens as the principal aspect of the contradiction.
That is to say, the invading pathogens are exuberant while the body defensive Qi is also strong or though the pathogens are excessive, the body defensive Qi does not decline yet. As a result, a fierce struggle is going on between them and obvious reactions appear with a series of pathological reactions of excess, known as excess syndrome.
It is often observed in the early or middle stage of an exogenic disease of in cases due to stagnation of phlegm, food, blood, water, etc. in the body.
Its clinical manifestations are: high fever, mania, high voice and strong breath, abdominal pain and tenderness, constipation, replete and forceful pulse, etc. in addition to some morbid conditions marked by excessive accumulation of phlegm and fluid-retention, indigestion of food, reverse flow of water within the body, stagnant blood, etc.
Under these circumstances a struggle between vitalQi and pathogens is going on, followed by a series of pathological reactions of deficiency, known as deficiency syndrome.
It is mostly seen in debilitated patients or in the later stage of a disease and in many chronic cases, clinically inarked by lassitude and thin and pallid complexion, palpitation, shortness of breath, spontaneous perspiration and night sweat, or dysphoria with feverish sensation in the chest, palms and soles, or aversion to cold, cold extremities, weak pulse, etc.
Wax or wane of vital Qi and pathogens can bring about not only pure excess syndrome or pure deficiency one, but also pathological changes of excess syndrome mixed with deficiency syndrome in some persistent and complicated diseases.
A combination of excess and deficiency syndromes comprises mainly two kinds of pathological changes: deficiency syndromes complicated with excess ones and excess syndromes complicated with deficiency ones.
Deficiency syndromes complicated with excess ones often result from inability to fight off pathogens due to insufficiency of vital Qi or due to stagnation of such pathological products as phlegm, food, blood and water within the body while excess syndromes complicated with deficiency ones are caused by impairment of vital Qi due to long term invasion by pathogens.
Hence, excess aspect or deficiency aspect of pathogenesis is merely relative, not absolute in the course of the development of a disease.
On the one hand, the appearance of genuine excess with pseudo-deficiency symptom, or appearance of deficiency in extreme excess" is caused by obstruction of the channels and collaterals and failure to transport Qi and blood outward due to accumulation of excess pathogens in the body.
Pseudo-excess symptom such as abdominal distention due to dysfunction of the spleen in transport pertains to a genuine deficiency with pseudo-excess syndrome.
From the above it can be seen that in analyzing an excess or deficiency syndrome of pathogenesis, we must see through the appearance to get at the es sence and only in so doing, can we not be misled by false phenomena and have a good grasp of logical changes of excess or deficiency syndrome.
After the onset of a disease, its recovery or development depends on the outcome of the struggle between vital Qi and pathogens.
The victory of vital Qi over pathogens tends towards improvement or even complete recovery of a disease.
Taking the febrile disease caused by exogenic pathogens for example, if vital Qi is adequate'enough to put up a powerful resistance against pathogens which invade the body through skin pores or via the mouth or nose, it can not only slow down further development of a disease and confine the lesions to superficial muscles or to channels and collaterals, but also expel the pathogens by means of its action on them. Once superficial syndrome is relieved by means of diaphoresis, the pathogens will be removed, harmony between nutritive Qi and defensive Qi reestablished and the disease will end in a complete cure.
As is known, recovery due to vital Qi's victory over pathogens is a common termination of a number of disorders; but if the pathogens are sufficient and vital Qi deficient, the former will win a victory over the latter and a reverse termination may happen to the disease, that is, the disease tends to deteriorate or to end fatally.
This is because vital Qi is deficient and pathogens are excessive and the body's resistance against pathogens is getting weaker and weaker with each passing day that vital Qi has difficulty checking their pathogenic action and further development and pathological lesions inflicted on the body are getting more serious, Consequently, the disease gradually deteriorates or aggravates.
Possession of vitality is a manifestation of abundant Qi-blood of the Zang-Fu organs.
The former results from congenital defect, lack of proper care after birth or dysfunction of the lungs, spleen and kidneys while the latter, from internal injury due to overfatigue or severe protracted illness. Deficiency of Qi, leading to hypofunction of various organs, is manifested by such symptons as listlessness, lassitude, spontaneous sweating, and susceptibility to cold.
For instance, deficiency of Qi results in inability to transport blood or diffuse body fluid, thus leading to their stagnation; inability to control blood and body fluid, thereby incurring their loss; and inability to generate them, thus bringing about their inadequate production.
Generally speaking, disorder of Qimay include the following five pathological changes: stagnation of Qi (its impeded circulation), reversed flow of Qi (its excessive upward flow and inadequate downward flow), collapse of Qi (its inadequate upward flow and excessive downward flow of Qi), blockage of Qi (obstruction of its external flow), and exhaustion of Qi (its external depletion instead of its retention inside the body).
It is due chiefly to emotional depression or stagnation of such pathological products as phlegm, food, blood, water, etc. which hinders the flow of Qi thus bringing about general or local disorders of disturbances of its functional activities with the resultant dysfunction of some Zang-Fu organs, channels and collaterals.
Stagnation of Qiat a certain spot willbring about abdominal distention and pain.
Generally, stagnancy of blood and retention of phlegm will inevitably lead to stagnation of Qi, which, in turn, well bring about the formation of the former.
It indicates a morbid condition in which the upward and downward flow of Qi is disturbed, marked by an upward adverse flow of Qi of the Zang-Fu organs.
The reversed flow of Qi is due mainly to emotional upset, improper cold or warm factors or stagnation of phlegm, etc., as is most frequently found in the lungs, stomach, liver, etc.
For example, adverse rising of the lung-Qi due to impairment of the lung's purifying and descending function is manifested by cough with dyspnea, adverse rising of the stomach-Qi due to its failure in descending, by nausea, vomiting, belching, hiccup etc., and the upward invasion of the hyperactive liver-Qi due to its excessive flow by headache, fullness of the head, flushed face and congested eyes, and irritability.
Generally, the reversed flow of Qi belongs to an excess syndrome, but is occasionally found in a deficiency syndrome.
Impairment of purifying and descending function due to deficiency syndrome of the lungs or failure of the kidneys in receiving Qi leads to the upward flow of Qi, as often seen in asthma of insufficiency type. This is the pathogenesis of the reversed flow of Qidue to deficiency syndrome.
Since the Zang-Fu organs depend on coordination of Qi's ascending or descending and incoming or outgoing movements for their relatively. fixed positions in the body, in case of decreased ability to ascend due to deficiency of Qi, ptoses of some of the Zang-organs will ensue, such as gastroprosis, nephroptosis, uterus ptosis and proctoptosis.
This syndrome is the result of external obstruction by turbid pathogens or obstruction of external flow by excessive stagnation of Qi, as manifested by syncope resulting from affection of Qi by turbid pathogens, that resulting from excessive heat in exogenic febrile diseases, and that resulting from sudden mental injury.
Since Qi is the most fundamental substance to maintain vital fucntional activities, the loss of a large amount of Qi gives rise to sudden failure of visceral function.
It is attributable chiefly to insufficient blood formation or its excessive consumption.
Its clinical symptoms are: pale complexiom, pale lips, dizziness, palpitation, lassitude, listlessness, emaciation, numbness of the extremities, impeded stretch and contraction of the joints, dryness and uncomfortable feeling of the eyes, vertigo, etc.
A dark red colour of the tongue proper is known as the crimson tongue, indicating heat syndrome and blood stasis.
Any one of the above five cases is enough to cause blood stasis and even resultant stagnant blood.
Therefore, the pathological changes caused by it, such as pain, fmass, are basically similar to those of stagnant blood.
And blood stasis may in turn aggravate the obstruction of functional activities of Qi, thereby forming a vicious cycle in which stagnation of Qi leads to blood stasis, which, in turn, leads to stagnation of Qi.
Consequently, stagnation Qi and blood stasis are often simultaneously seen in the course of a disease.
Specifically, it may be caused by blood stasis due to stagnation of Qi, or stagnation of Qi due to accumulation of blood in the interior or simultaneous formation of both due to trauma by sprain and contusion.
Since the liver's dredging function plays a key role in the regulation of the functional activities of Qi, stagnation of Qi and blood stasis are closely concerned with the physiological dysfunction of the liver.
Again, with the heart responsible for the circulation of blood, its physiological dysfuncion leads first to blood stasis and then to stagnancy of Qi, both marked by such symptoms as distending pain, ecchymosis and abdominal mass,
Because Qi is derived from the spleen, its dysfunction in transport will cause deficiency of Qi due to inadequate production of Qi.
Since Qi can control the blood circulation, deficiency of Qi will bring about bleeding because it's too weak to control the flow of blood.
In addition, since the spleen dominates upward flow of Qi deficiency of Qi in the middle-Jiao and its sinking will bring about escape of blood from the lower part of the body, as is often seen in such symptoms as metrorrhagia and blood stool.
It's usually brought about by massive loss of blood due to trauma or metrorrhagia and postpartum hemorrhage.
With blood as the carrier of Qi, exhaustion of blood leads to the loss of the carrier on which Qi depends, and therefore, Qi is exhausted together with blood.
As a result. exhaustion of Qi and blood brings about sudden severe functional failure of the human body.
It is a morbid state showing coexistence of deficiency of both Qi and blood, resulting from consumption of both Qi and blood after protracted illness, or loss of blood followed by consumption of Qi, decreased production of blood due to deficiency of Qi.
Clinically, it is manifested simultaneously by such deficiency syndromes as pale or yellowish complexion, shortness of breath, disinclination for talk, fatigue and weakness, emaciation, palpitation, insomnia or numbness of the limbs.
If Qi and blood are sufficient enough to interact on each other, tendons and muscles, well nourished, can function to facilitate movements of the limbs, and the skin, well nourished, can experience sensattions normally.
Conversely, if the channels, tendons, muscles and skin are not properly nourished due to deficiency of Qi and blood, or derangement of Qi and blood dyskinesia or paresthesia, e.g.numbness of the limbs, or even paralysis of the limbs, itching, and dryness of the skin, or even dry and squamous skin may ensue as a result.
By disturbance in fluid metabolism is meant disturbance of its distribution and imbalance between its production and excretion, thus resulting in insufficiency of body fluid due to reduced production, excessive consumption and excretion, or in such pathologic changes as fluid retention, stagnation and overflow brought about by sluggish fluid circulation within the body.
From the viewpoint of pathogenesis, insufficiency of body fluid is divided into two phases:(1) impairment of Jin and (2) exhaustion of Ye.
Distribution and discharge of body fluid are the two important links in the process of matabolism of body fluid, and func tional disturbance of these links may lead to retention of body fluid within the body, which is then transformed into phlegm and dampness.
Body fhuid depends on the lungs'dispersing and descending function for its transformation into sweat to be excreted, and on the functioning of the kidney-Qi for its transformation into urine to be discharged.
Therefore, discharge disturbance of body fluid resuls mainly from functional disturbance of the lungs and kidneys.
Water retention and stangation of Qi can be the cause or effect of each other alternatively in that the former can give rise to the latter and vice versa.
Its common causes are: consumption of body fluid by high fever, or profuse perspiration, or severe vomiting, or diarrhea.
As the saying goes:"Qi cannot be kept intact after vomiting or diarrhea".
Body fluid and blood, derived from the same source, are mutually permeable. Body fluid is an important component of blood.
As the transformation occurs inside the body, they are also referred to as endogenous wind, endogenous cold, endogenous dampness, endogenous dryness, and endogenous fire, respectilvely coming under the general term "five endogenous pathogens".
It is also referred to as liver-wind or.liver-wind stirring inside the body, for its occurrence is closely related to the liver.
Its clinical manifestations are: convulsion, hyperphoria, accompanied by high fever, coma, delirium, etc., often seen in the climax of a febrile disease,
It indicates endopathic wind of deficiency type stirring up inside, brought about by failure of insufficient liver blood to nourish tendons and vessels, or failure of blood to nourish collaterals, resulting from decreased production of blood, or massive loss of blood, or protracted illness which impairs blood.
Its clinical manifestations are: dryness of the skin or dry and squamous skin, accompanied by itching or desquamation of skin, etc.
It indicates the morbid condlition of retention of water and phlegm within the body, caused by disturbance of the spleen's transporting and distributing function.
In addition, Blockage of the middle-Jiao by dampness is marked by abdominal distention, poor appetite, greasy taste or sweat taste in the mouth, thick greasy fur of the tongue, etc.
Endogenous dryness is commonly seen in the lungs, stomach and large intestine. In addition to the symptoms mentioned above, lung-dryness as the main symptom is also accompanied by dry cough without sputum, or even hemoptysis, while stomach-dryness as the main symptom is followed by reddened tongue without fur. Lastly, in case of intestine-dryness there will be constipation.
Secondly, pathologic products of the body, such as phlegm, stagnated blood, malnutrition due to parasitic infestation, food retention, all can accumulate to be trasformed into fire.
The main influence it has on the physiologic functions of the heart may be summarized as follows:(1) It disturbs the mind.
(2) It causes biood-heat and swift blood flow.
(3) It gives rise to flaring-up or moving-down of the heart-fire.
As the tongue is the orifice of the heart, it can reflect the physiological and pathological states of the latter. If the heart-fire flames upward along the large collaterals. there will be such symptoms as ulceration of the mouth and tongue, burning pain at the tip of the tongue, dry mouth and nose, etc. On the other hand the heart is interior-exteriorly related to the small intestine.
Clinically, there appears to be listlessness, weakened mental state, slow response, drowsiness, disinclination to talk, low voice, etc.
(2) Blood stagnation due to cold.
When fire of deficiency type disturbs the mind, there may appear such manifestations as irritability and insomnia.
Deficiency of the heartblood leads to reduced blood circulation marked by smail weak pulse, and to neurosis due to inability to nourish the mind, manifested as inability to concentrate attention, or even trance.
Poor supply of nutrition to the face due to blood deficiency is manifested by dim complexion and dryness of the tongue.
And as a result of failure of blood to noursh the heart, there may appear such symptoms as palpitation, or even panic.
Stagnation of the heart-blood, or blockage of the heart vessels, refers to the pathologic changes marked by stagnation of blood in the heart vessels due to impeded circulation of blood.
Due to obstruction of the heart vessels and impeded blood circulation, there may appear such symptoms as oppressed sensation and pain in the chest.
It usually results from consumption of the lung-Qi by protracted illness or overstrain, or from prolonged impairment of the lung's dispersing and descending function.
Generally speaking, exogenous pathogens often impair the lung's dispersing function, leading to obstruction of the lung-Qi, while internal injury affects the lung's purifying and descending function, leading to their dysfunction.
Obstruction of the lung-Qi results in dysfunction of the lung-Qi and impairment of the lung's respiratory function, marked by nasal obstruction, chest stuffiness, or anhidrosis due to stagnation of the defensive Qi and obstruction of superficies.
If reduced dispersing function of the lung's results from deficiency of the lung-Qi, it is manifested by spontaneous perspiration due to lowered the body resistance.
Insufficiency of the spleen-Qi, also refered to as Qi-insufficiency of. the middle-Jiao, is mostly caused by dysfunction of the spleen due to improper diet, by congenital weak constitution, by consumption after prolonged illness, or by overstrain.
Deficiency of the spleen-Qi results in impaired transporting-transforming function of the spleen, manifested as indigestion and tastelessness in the mouth, while deficiency of the spleen proper also leads to impairment of its function in sending up essential substances, which, in turn, affects the function of the stomach to send digested food downward, manifested in the upper part of the body as dizziness, in the middle part as distension in epigastrium, and in the lower part as loose stool and diarrhea.
Dysfunction of the spleen due to its deficiency deprives Qi and blood of their source, of growth and development, leading to systemic insussiciency of Qi and blood.
Moreover, deficiency of the spleen also impairs its function in governing blood, manifested by loss of blood, such as hemafecia, metrorrhagia, metrostaxis, etc.
Finally, deficiency of the spleen-Qialso weakens its lifting function, or even causes its collapse, manifested by such pathological manifestations as prolapse of rectum due to lingering diarrhea, ptosis of internal organs, etc.
As a result of impairment of the spleen's transporting and transforming function, there may appear such symptoms as abdominal distention, loose stool, indigestion, etc. As a result of insufficiency of body fluid, there may appear symptoms such as dry mouth and tongue, and reddish tongue with little fur.
It is caused by sluggish functional activities of the liver-Qi due to dysfunction of the liver resulting from emotional upset or depression. In the affected area there may appear distending pain, e. g., bilateral hypochondriac fullness, or pain in the right hypochondrium etc.
If stagnation of Qi combines with that of phlegm or blood, in the affected area there may appear lumps, manifested in the upper part as goiter and globus hystericus; in the middle part as lumps with distending pain in the breast, in the lower part as lower abdominal pain, bearing-down and distending pain in the testis, etc.
Moreover, stagnation of the liver-Qi and its transverse invasion of the stomach lead to adverse rising of the stomach-Qi, manifested as belching, and acid regurgitation. In case of transverse invasion of the spleen by the hyperactive liver-Qi diarrhea with pain occurs as a result.
It is brought about by upward movement of the liver-fire which is transformed from the depressed liver-Qi, by violent rage which impairs the liver, leading to the rise of the liver-fire; or by the movement of the liver-fire transformed from five emotions in excess.
Moreover, deficiency of blood may also give rise to dryness-transformation leading to stirring up of wind of deficiency type, manifested by such pathological manifestations as itch, clonic spasm of muscle due to trauma or cramp.
Insufficiency of the kidnely-essence may retard the growth and development of infants, or delay the be. ginning of menstrual function and impede the development and maturiity of sexual glands at puberty, or lead to senilism and hyposexuality among the middle-aged, marked by impotence and spermatorrhea.
If insufficiency of the kidney-essence affects the sea of marrow (brain), there may appear such clinical manifestations as mental retardation, bradypragia, flaccidity of the legs, etc.
As a result of dysfunction of the kidneys, unconsolidation of the kidney-Qi leads to inability to control defecation and urination, manifested as fecal and urinous incontinence and enuresis.
This morbid state impairs the air-receiving function of the kidneys, and dyspnea occurs even on slight exertion.
It leads to weakened function of the stomach in receiving and transforming food, thereby resulting in such pathological manifestations as poor appetite, tastelessness in the mouth, or even anorexia.
It also leads to dysfunction of the stomach in transporting food downward marked by fullness in epigastrium or even belching nausea, vomiting, and hiccup due to adverse rising of the stomach-Qi.
It also leads obviously to dysfunction of the stomach in transforming food into chyme, marked by indigestion.
When the fire flares up along the channels, it gives rise to gingivitis or gingival hemorrhage.
TCM holds that the human body is an organic whole whose component parts are physiologically interconnected and pathologically interacted and that the local lesions may affect the entire body and disorders of internal organs, in turn, may manifest themselves in various aspects of the body surface, such as the five sense organs, the extremities and so on.
Since the face and the tongue have close relation to the five Zang-organs and the six Fu-organs, and the vicissitudes of the Zang-Fu-organs can be most easily reflected by the appearance and colour of these location, they are the commonest and the most principal places for observation.
Inspection of the superficial venules of the infant's index finger, as a special diagnostic method in peadiatrics, is of great significance in the diagnosis of childhood diseases.
This refers to inspection of patient's vicissitudes of vitality, vitality, a general term for life processes of the human body, involves two aspects:(1) the outward manifestations of all life activities, and (2) thought and consciousness, vitality exists in the physique without which there will be no vitality.
Hence, sound vitality dwells in healthy physique, and, conversely, diseased physique can certainly lead to abnormal vitality. As a result, the vicissitudes of vitality are an important mark of whether or not the physique is healthy.
Vitalty may be manifested in manifold aspects, especially in the eyes. Therefore, observation of vitality is focused on the patient's eyes, facial expression and behavior.
Possession of vitality or vigour, is a manifestation of abundant Qi-blood of the Zang-Fu-orangs, commonly seen in a healthy person.
When seen in a patient, it implies a mild illness without serious damage of the vital Qi, often accompanied by a favorable prognosis. Its manifestations are: full consciousness, clear utterance, bright eyes, lustrous face, sharp response, natural posture, easy breath, fine-looking flesh, and regular urination and defecation.
Among them, full consciousness and clear utterance result from sufficient vital essence of the heart; bright eyes, sharp response and natural posture from abundant vital essence of the liver and kidneys; and easy breath and fine-looking flesh from abundant vital essence of the spleen and lungs.
In short, possession of vitality is a manifestation of abundant vital essence and active life activities.
Loss of vitality is a manifestation of the impairment of the vital essence and Qi in the Zang-Fu organs.
Its main manifestations are: unconsciousness, apathetic expression, dull look in the eyes, lustreless complexion, sluggish response, faint breath, emaciation.
Among them, unconsciousness, apathetic expression and lustreless complexion are caused by exhaustion of vital essence of the heart; dull look in the eyes and sluggish response by exhaustion of vital essence of the live and kidneys; faint breath by exhaustion of vital essence of the lungs; and emaciation by exhaustion of vital essence of the spleen.
Colour and lustre are regarded as the outward manifestation of ability of Qi-blood in the Zang-Fu organs to nourish body surface. TCM holds that the complexion of a healthy person is shiny and lustrous, and is considered normal, as long as it remains so even though it differs much in different races, natural endowment and some physiological functions. The complexion of a patient in a morbid state is said to be sickly which is characterized by darkness and lustrelessness, or excessive brighteness and distinctness, or failure to correspond to appro priate seasons and relevant regions of the Zang-Fu-organs in spite of its brightness and lustre.
The white complexion is manifestation of deficiency of both Qi and blood and their poor supply to the face, indicating deficiency syndrom, cold sydrome and loss of blood.
The yellow complexion s frequently related to a spleen disorder and is a manifestation of dysfunction of the spleen in trans- port, retention of water within the body or deficiency of Qi and blood.
Moreover, stagnation of Qi and blood. leads to pain and malnutrition of the tendons and vessel, to convulsion and spasm. Therefore, the bluish complexion is a sign of cold syndrome, pain syndroms, blood stasis and convulsion.
The red collateral at the back of the auricle, accompanied by the cold sulcus auriculae posterior, is often considered as a premonitory symptom of measles. Squamous and dry helix is seen in blood stasis formed in a protracted disease or in acute appendicitis. Profuse cerumen blocking external acoustic meatus is known as ceruminosis, and pus flowing in the ear, yellow, white or reddish in colour as otopysis, or otitis media suppurative, resulting mostly from the upward invasion of wind-heat or damp-heat in the liver and gallbladder.
The red and swollen nose with sores is a sign of blood--heat. A stuffy nose due to nasal polyp is attributable to extreme heat in the lungs or stagnation of wind-dampness. The flushing apex nasi with acnes, named rosacea, is usually caused by the pathogenic heat in the spleen and stomach spreading to the blood stream.
The disorders of the lungs, stomach and kidneys may be reflected on the throat, observation of which aims chiefly at finding out whether there are redness and swelling, white membrane and its liquid secretion on the pharynx and larynx.
The bright paint-like red skin is seen in erysipelas due to invasion of blood by the heart-fire and pathogenic wind -heat. The red and swollen lower limbs indicate the downward flow of damp-heat; and the yellow-brown pigmentation of the skin can be seen in jaundice. The moist and lustrous skin suggests plenty of body fluid in the lungs, but, on the contrary, the dry skin with shedding of the vellus hairs, inadequacy of body fluid.
The red discolored patch on the skin that is located not above it is known as macula by the outward dispersion of the pathogenic heat in the lungs and stomach from the muscles, white the red and millet-like spots located above the skin, as papula caused by outward dispersion of the pathogenic heat in the lungs and stomach from the skin.
Therefore, miliaria alba is referred to as a manifestation of outward flow of the stagnated dampness.
In morbid condition, the plump-eared miliaria, whitish in color and small in size, is called crystalline miliaria suggesting a favorable prognosis because of the abundance of vital Qi, conversely, the shrivelled miliaria without any fluid in it is called dried miliaria indicating an unfavorable prognosis of a serious case due to exhaustion of body fluid.
Moreover the miliaria occurring in the damp-warm syndrome probably repeatedly, because it is difficult for miliaria alba to erupt thoroughly due to blockage of the retained heat by dampness.
By observation of the tongue a physician can predict the vicissitudes of vital Qi, detect the depth of the location of illness, determine the nature of pathogenic factors, and infer the severity of disease.
Hence, it plays an extremely important role in diagnosis in TCM.
The tongue proper or the tongue body, consists of muscles, vessels, channels and collaterals in the tongue Owing to its connections with many viscera through the meridians, the tongue proper relies on Qi and blood and body fluid transformed by the Zang-Fu organs for warmth and nutrition, thus the condition of vital essence of the Zang-Fu organs can be learned by observing the mobility colour, size, shape of the tongue proper. As a result, inspection of the tongue body is of great importance in making diagnosis and predicting of disease.
A tongue lighter than normal is known as pale tongue which principally indicates cold syndrome of insufficiency type and deficiency of both Qi and blood.
It is a manifestation of fullness of collateral vessels with blood surge due to overabundance of heat.
Since the puffiness of the tongue is due to retention of water-damp within the tongue body caused by dysfunction of the spleen in transport the indented tongue mainly indicates hypofunction of the spleen and excessive dampness.
This morbid tongue is chiefly seen in appolexy or premonitory symptoms of apoplexy due to an attack of the pericardium by excessive heat with body fluid involved and stagnation of phlegm in the interior.
To sum up, the deep red and stiff tongue usually indicates intense heat, the puffy and stiff tongue with the thick greasy fur often suggests phlegm -dampness, and pink or bluish-purplish tongue with rigidity is mostly seen in apoplexy.
The wagging tongue is a collective term for the protruding tongue and played tongue, both of which are caused by pathogenic heat in the heart and spleen, with the former referring to frequent protrusion of the tongue and the latter to slight protrusion and frequent draw back of the tongue, or lick of the lips and corners of the mouth by the tongue.
Generally speaking, the tongue moving incessantly indicates the excessive heat in the heart and spleen leading to occurrence of eind syndrome with consumption of body fluid.
The frequent protrusion of the tongue is usually seen in cases of attack of the heart by the pestilential heat or exhaustion of the vital Qi often accompanied by the bluish-purplish tongue proper, and playing with the tongue is considered as a sign of wind syndrome, mostly seen as a premonitory sign of convulsions or in infants with congenital hypoplasia with poor mental development, or in idiotic infants with mental retardation.
A tongue turning to one side involuntarily while protruding is called the wry tongue, in most cases with marked inclination of the anterior half of the tongue to either the left or the right side.
This morbid tongue is mostly caused by obstruction of the collaterals on one side of the tongue body due to the liver-wind stirring up inside the body with upward stagnation of phlegm or phlegm-blood stasis.
Since the muscles on the affected side of the tongue are sluggish and weak and those on the healthy side contract normally, the tongue turns to the healthy side while protruding, indicating apoplexy or a premonitory sign of apoplexy.
The tongue fur is a layer of fur-like substance covering the surface of the tongue and formed under the steaming action of the stomach-Qi.
Observation of the tongue fur includes that of the proper of the fur and that of color of the longue coating.
A normal fur, white in colour and even in distribution is spread thinly on the surface of the tongue, with its root underneath preventing it from being sticky and greasy.
On the other hand, a morbid tongue fur is caused by invasion by exogenous pathogens or retention of phlegm and food inside the body.
Inspection of the tongue fur is mainly made by observing its colour, moisture, thickness, appearance and distribution in combination with ob servation of the tongue proper. It is one of the important parts of tongue inspection, which furnishes information about the condi. tion of body fluid as well as the nature and location of pathogens.
In the latter case, however, the white, moist fur spreading over the tongue like the heaped powder, but not being dry while palpated is called the powder-like fur, as a result of affection by exogenous filthy-turbid pathogens or excessive pathogenic heat in the body. It is often seen in pestilence of abscess of internal organs. In addition, the white and dry fur like sand, being rough while palpated, is due to sudden onset of inter. nal heat and swift cbnsumption of body fluid, leading to failure of the white fur to be in time transformed into yellow because of rapid conversion of the epidemic febrile disease into heat.
The former is formed by upward aggregation of body fluid on the tongue surface due to upward steaming of the stomach-Qi, and the latter, however, by upward retention of phlegm-dampness and food-drink on the surface of the tongue due to rising up of the stomach-Qi.
The former is mostly seen in a healthy person or a patient having an exterior syndrome with the fur left unchanged, while the latter, in most cases, suggests an interior syndrome due to retention of phlegm, dampness, food and others in the gaslrointestinal tract.
The fur gettig thicker and thicker indicates uniavorable pronos is due to aggravation of a disease owing to exuberant pathogens. On the contrary, the fur getting thinner and thinner suggests a favorable prognosis due to predominance of vital Qi and gradual decline of the pathogen.
In short, the severity and location of the pathogens can be judged by the thickness of the tongue fur.
In some special circumstances, the dry fur may also be seen in dampness syndrome, and the glossy fur in dryness syndrome.
A furless tongue as smooth as a mirror is named mirror-like tongue; the partly exfoliating fur only with the center of the tongue surface coated is called chicken heart-like fur; the exfoliating fur as interlocking as a map is known as a map-like tongue; and a scanty and scattered fur on the tongue surfa? is called lingua geographica.
On the contrary, the regeneration of a thin and white fur after being stripped off is regarded as favorable sign of conquest of pathogens by vital Qi and gradual recovery of the stomach-Qi.
Fluids secreled from the ears, nose, mouth and eyes are known as secretions, whereas waste materials eliminated from the body as excretions.
Generally speaking, the clear and watery discharges indicate deficiency syndrome and cold syndrome, whereas the dark (or red) and thick discharges, heat syndrome and excess syndrome. In addition, the blackish discharges mingled with some lumps of objects are usually attributable to blood stasis.
Vomiting due to different causes can produce vomitus of different shape and nature and different accompanying symptoms and signs.
Loose stool and diarrhea with indigested food or stool resembling duck feces are due to disturbance of the spleen by cold-dampness or insufficiency of Qi of both the spleen and the stomach, bringing about their dysfunction in transportation and transformation and retention of body fluid in the intestines due to their failure to receive and transport foodstuffs; dark yellow, foul and sticky stool indicates accumulation of dampheat in the intestines; red-white mixed and mucous stool is brought about by dysentery due to accumulation of pathogenic damp-heat in the large intestine and intrusion upon both Qi and blood; the whitish stool with profuse pus indicates excessive dampness in the Qisystem; and the dark purplish blood defecated following feces implies bleeding from distant part known as"distant bleeding"due to weakness of the spleen and stomach, while bright red blood defecated before feces is called"nearby bleeding", often seen in hemorrhage from hemorrhoids, and anal fissure or hemalochezia due to impairment of the lung collaterals by pathogenic wind-heat.
Urine mixed with blood is called"stranguria complicated by hematuria"; cloudy urine like oil is often known as "stranguria marked by chyluria"; and urine mixed with sand-like or stonelike objects accompanied by burning pain in the urethra on micturition and urinary stuttering is often referred to as "stranguria due to urinary stone".
This method is mainly used in children under three years of age because of their tender skin, which makes the venules quite visible.
Normal superficial venules of the index finger are near the transverse crease between the palm and the index finger, and extending from the proximal to the outside are Fengguan (wind-pass). Qiguan (Qi-pass) and Mingguan (life-pass) refering to the superficial venules visible on the proximal, middle and distant segment of the infant's index finger, and becoming reddish and faintly visible on the proximal middle and distant segment respectively.
To sum up, the superficial venules emerging at Fengguan, Qiguan and Mingguan are indicative of a mild, serious and critical condition respectively.
Visible venules indicate the exterior syndrome, often seen in diseases due to exogenous pathogens; and invisible venules, the interior syndrome. Thin and light-coloured venules often denote deficiency syndrome and thick and dark-coloured venules, excess syndrome.
The emerging degree of the superficial venules is also affected by the thickness and colour of skin, and the type of build as well.
For example, the thin skin, where venules are easily visible, shows supersficial venules, and the thick skin, deep venules. A fat person presents deep venules while a thin person, superficial ones. Consequently diagnosis can only be made in combination with other clinical data.
According to traditional Chinese medicine, all the sounds and odors from the human body, produced in the course of physiological and pathological activities of Zang-Fu organs, may reflect their physiological and pathological changes.
Here, listening consists mainly of that of various changes of the patient's speech or voice (high or low, strong or weak), as well as abnormal sounds accompanying cough, vomiting, hiccup or eructation, etc. in order to determine the nature of a disease, such as cold or heat syndrome, and deficiency or excess syndrome; while smelling involves that of various odors of the patient's body, mouth and such excretions as sweat and phlegm in order to differentiate diseases.
The pectoral Qi has also a close relation with the voice due to its capability of promoting respiration.
Once normal activities of Qi are affected whetber by exogenous pathogens or by internal injury, or vocal organs are affected, the voice is likely to become abnormal. As a result, listening to the voice can detect changes of internal organs and the body as a whole.
Low voice speaking accompanied by stuffy and running nose and chilliness without sweating are indicative of affection by exogenous wind-cold; deep and indistinct voice associated with the feeling of oppression over the epigastrium and heaviness sensation of the limbs are caused by retention of pathogenic dampness; moaning and screaming are seen in pain-syndrome; hoarseness in a new disorder is due to invasion of the epiglottis by pathogens; phònia after prolonged disease suggests insufficiency of the lungs and kidneys, and huskiness during pregnancy is mostly considered normal.
For instance, feeble breathing with lack of strength for respiration is called insufficiency of Qi, often due to deficiency off vital Qi of both the lungs and kidneys. Strong coarse and loud breathing is called rude respiration brought about by accumulation of pathogenic heat in the lungs; rapid shallow breathing or difficulty in respiration, even with opened mouth and elevated shoulders, flaring of nares and inability to lie flat, is called dyspnea which is classified into excess-type and deficiency-type, the former referring to loud and coarse breathing with comfortable sensation upon expiration and the latter to weak and low breathing with difficulty in going on respiration.
Cough is a manifestation of impairment of purifying and descending function of the lungs leading to adverse rising of the lung-Qi.
Listening to cough, a doctor should focus his attention on cough sound and changes in amount, colour and quality of the sputum in order to differentiate cold or heat syndrome, and deficiency or excess syndrome of a disease.
The smell of sweat given off from the body im. plies having a perspiration; sweating with smelling of fish or mutton is caused by accumulation of damp-heat in the skin. Fetid odor from nose, with continual turbid nose discharge is often indicative of sinusitis; and expectoration of foul sputum with pus and blood indicates the lung abscess.
Fetid stool pertains to heat syndrome while stinking stool to cold syndrome.
Through inquiring, doctors can know the patient's case history, subjective symptoms, family history, therapeutic measures already taken, and especially some kinds of diseases without signs which can only be detected by questioning.
During questioning, a doctor should first watch out for the patient's main sufferings, around which he carries on the interrogation purposefully step by step with special emphasis on comprehensive study as well as on key information.
Chilliness is the patient's subiective symptom, and fever refers to an undue rise in body temperature or to the patient's sensation of heat.
Alternate chills and fever at irregular intervals. often accompanied by bitter taste in the mouth, dry throat, dizziness, etc, are due to a lingering of the pathogens between the exterior and the interior with a stalemating conflict between the vital Qi and pathogens. The alternate attack of shivers with cold and high fever once a day, or every other day or every three days is called malaria, accompanied by a serious headache, thirst and profuse sweating etc.
The tendons, muscles and skin depend for their nourishment on Qi and blood, which circulate through channels.
Anhidrosis or hyperhidrosis occurs due to invasion of pathogens or deficiency of vital Qi during the disease.
It is a turning point of the development of pathological changes and of a conflict between vital Qi and pathogens and also a manifestation of accumulated vital Qi in its struggle for eliminating pathogens.
The sweating side is in a healthy condition, which indicates normal functioning of nutrient Qi and defensive Qi which can govern the open-cose of pores regularly, while the side without sweating is the affected one, caused by blockage of channels, and obstruction of nutrient Qi and defensive Qi as well as incoordination between Qi and blood.
Firstly, it is caused by stagnant Qi and blood due to blockage of the meridians. In most cases, it is brought about by invasion of exogenous pathogens or Qi stagnancy and blood stasis, or coagulated phlegm all of which lead to pain of excess type.
Secondly, it results from malnutrition of Zang-Fu organs and tissues due to deficiency of Qi and blood. This is pain of deficiency type.
Different nature, location and intensity of pain reflect different nature of pathogens and affected portions of the body. From the above it follows that the stress of questioning should be laid on nature, location, intensity of questioning pain and the patient's likes or dislikes as well.
Headache may be caused by either exogenous pathogens or internal injury.
Owing to different distribution of the channels in the head, the affected channel can be detected according to the location of pain.
Moderate intermittent headache running a long course usually pertains to pain caused by internal injury, lingering headache, aggravated on exertion, to headache due to Qi-insufficiency; pain accompanied by dizziness and pale complexion. to headache due to blood-deficiency, and that accompanied by an empty sensation in the head and lassitude in the loins and knees, to headache due to kidney-deficiency which is caused by insufficiency of kidney-essence and inability of the brain to be nourished.
Since the liver and gallbladder are situated in the hypochondriac region, hypochondriac pain is related to these two organs.
The former, situated above umbilicus, contains the liver, gallbladder, spleen and stomach. Pain in the upper abdomen is often related to these organs.
The latter, located below umbilicus, comprises the kidneys, bladder, large and small intestines, and the uterus. Pain in the lower abdomen is often related to the above-mentioned organs, while that in the bilateral lower abdomen, which the liver channels pass by, is usually related to the liver.
There is also pain o limbs which fail to be nourished due to weakness of the stomact and spleen. If the pain is located only in the heel with lassitude and soreness in the loins and legs, it is usually attributable to deficiency of the kidneys.
Intermittent and migrating distending pain of the chest, hypochondrium, epigastrium and abdomen is usually due to the stagnation of Qiwhich is closely related to the function of the liv. er to govern normal flow of Qi.
Pain with heaviness sensation is usually caused by stagnation of Qi due to pathogenic dampness often appearing in the head, limbs and loins, because dampness is liable to block the functioning of Qi due to its properties of turbidity and viscosity.
Violent pain as if cutting by knife is generally caused by sudden blockage of Qi due to substantial pathogens or coagulation by pathogenic cold.
Colicky pain in the precordial area is called "real cardiac pain"due to obstruction of heart channels; abdominal colicky pain with visible mass, even vomiting of roundworms results from upward disturbance of ascaris, and colicky pain in the lower abdomen accompanied by urine with sand and stone or a sudden stop of urination indicates stranguria due to urinary stone. In addition, attack of the stomach and intestines by pathogenic cold can also give rise to colicky pain in the abdomen.
Dull and mild pain is due to deficiency of Qi and blood leading to inability of organs and tissues to be warned, belonging to deficiency syndrome, often seen in chronic consumptive diseases which are characterized by lingering pain and a long course.
Difficulty in falling asleep during the night or waking easily from sleep or even inability to sleep all night long is known as insomnia.
Dysuria with the puffy body is a condition called edema. Frequent urination is often due to retention of dampness in the lower-Jiao or unconsolidation of the kidney-Qi. Retention of urine leads to a condition known as anuria often caused by dampness-heat, blood stasis or urinary stone, whereas difficult and painful urination is called stranguria.
Dysfunction of the spleen in transportation may lead to endogenous dampness due to deficiency of the spleen.
Involuntary shaking of head is mostly brought about by wind syndrome or malnutrition of the brain due to deficiency of Qi and blood. Dense black hair with luster is an indication of adequacy of vital essence. Sparse yellow hair with dryness and withering is mostly seen after a serious disease. Sudden and extensive loss of hair is usually caused by blood-heat with invasion of wind.
The infants are liable to be frightened since their minds are not fully developed. They are also susceptible to indigestion because of weakness of the spleen and stomach; and are prone to be affected by seasonal pathogens due to inadaptability to changes in the weather.
Firstly, it refers to a diagnostic method of general pulse-feelings described for the first time in Huangdi Neijing ("Yellow Emperor's Internal Classic of Medicine").
In other werds there are altogether nine parts of the body to be palpated for diagnostic purposes.
Secondly. it refers to the pulse-taking on Cunkou, which is a general term for the three pulse locations on the wrist over the radial artery, namely Cun, Guan, and Chi, and each location is palpated with light, moderate and heavy pressure respectively to get nine aspects of the pulse condition.
Cun, Guan and Chi (inch, bar and cubit) are the three places on the wrist over the radial artery where the pulse is felt.
The best time for pulse-feeling is the early morning because the patient is then less affected by food intake and other activities and Qi and blood in meridians are less disturbed so that it is easy to recognize patient's real pulse.
(2) Position of the body The patient is required to sit or lie flat on the back with the arm extending, the palm facing upward, and the forearm being on nearly the same level as the heart in order to keep Qi and blood flowing freely.
Meanwhile, the cloth pillow should be placed under the patient's wrist for convenience of pulse-feeling.
Use just one finger (index finger or thumb) to feel the pulse for children over 3 years, and observation of the superficial venules of their index fingers is made instead of pulse-feeling for infants under 3 years.
(4) Manipulations Pulse-taking is made by pressing the arteries with the palmar surfaces of the three fingers which are slightly bent like bows so that the tips of the three fingers are at the same level.
Firstly, the finger force is exerted lightly, a procedure named touching, then moderate force is applied, which is called searching, and finally heavier pressure is exerted i.e. pressing. Another meaning of"searching" is to vary the force or move the fingers to get a more distinct pulse-reading.
The three fingers are simultaneously used to feel pulse; this procedure is called general pressing.
In order to recognize the pulse condition of one particular portion, one of the three fingers can be used alone to feel pulse.
(5) Duration of pulse-taking 3-5 Minutes are enough for each feeling and the minimum time for pulse-feeling should be no less than one minute.
Normal pulse refers to the pulse condition of a healthy person, characterized by its stomach-Qi, vitality and root, When the pulse is moderate, unhurried, calm and regular, it is said to have the stomach-Qi.
The soft, even and forceful pulse indicates the vitality.
If the forceful pulse can be taken on deep palpation, especially at the Chi, it is said to have root.
Normal pulse must have these three features, which indicate adequacy and harmony of Qi-blood as well as sound mind and body.
Therefore, detection of the stomach-Qi, vitality and root in pulse condition has certain clinical significance in the.improvement or deterioration and favorable or unfavorable prognosis of a disease.
For exampie, owing to seasonal variations, the pulse in spring is sormewhat taut; in summer somewhat full; in autumn somewhat floating and in winter somewhat deep.
An anatomic anormaly of the radial artery which makes the pulse beat running from the Chi (cubit) area laterally and obliquely to Hukou (near point Hegu) on the back of the hand is called slantly located radial pulse, while radial pulse palpable at the dorsum of the wrist in an anormaly of the radial artery is named ectopic radial pulse.
All these pulses mentioned obove are thought of as physiological variations rather than abnormal pulses.
Floating pullse one which can be felt only by light touch and grows faint on pressing hard, usualy indicating exterior syndrome and deficiency syndrome as well.
It is often seen in the common cold and in the early stage of some acute febrile diseases, in which the defensive Qi resists outwards the pathogens on the body surface and thus channel-Qi becomes more superficial.
Scattered pulse is a pulse condition with scattered and disordered beats but without root which can be felt only by light touch and become impalpable by heavy pressure, seen in critical cases, showing depletion of primordial Qi and exhaustion of Qi of Zang-Fu-organs.
Deep pulse is a pulse condition in which the beats are located deeply and hardly felt by light touch but become distinct by hard pressure, indicating interior syndrome.
Hidden pulse is one felt only on pressing the bone hard located even deeper than deep pulse, and seen in cases of syncope, severe pains resulting from accumulation of pathogens in the in. terior of the body which bring about the obstructions of Qi and blood.
Moderate pulse is one characterized by four beats to one cyce of respiration, with even rhythm and moderate tension, and seen in damp syndrome in which dampness obstructs Qi-blood in circulation, or weakness of the spleen and stomach which fail to promote the normal flow of Qi-bleod.
The pulse of a patient beating gently and moderately indicates the recovery of the patient's vital Qi, and that beating unhurriedly, gently and regularly is said to be a pulse condition of a healthy person.
Rapid and strong pulse indicates excess-heat syndrome; while rapid and feeble pulse, deficiency-heal syndrome.
In a word, swift pulse is indicative of an extremely critical condition.
This is a general term for all forceless pulses that feel soft, weak and hollow, when either lightly pressing or heavily pressing on Cun, Guan and Chi, indicating deficiency syndrome, often seen in deficiency of both Qi and blood and weakness of Zang-Fu organs, especially in insufficiency of Qi which is unable to promote circulation of blood, further leading to emptiness of vessels.
Replete pulse, a general term for all vigorous pulses, feels vigorous and forceful at the three portions on both light and hard pressure, indicating excess syndrome, in which overabundant pathogens struggle against the strong vital Qi, giving rise to stagnation of Qi and blood and excessive repletion of the channels.
Slippery pulse is one coming and going smoothly, feeling slick to the finger like beads rolling on a plate, indicating excess-heat syndrome, phlegm retention and dyspepsia.
The slippery and moderate pulse occurring in a healthy person suggests plentitude and free flow of nutritive Qi and defensive-Qi.
In addition, it is also seen in a pregnant woman and shows the adequacy and harmony of Qi and blood.
A pulse, coming and going unsmoothly, like scraping bamboo with a knife, is called hesitant pulse, the condition of which is just the opposite of slippery pulse.
A pulse, hesitant and forceless, indicates deficiency of essence and blood which leads to the emptiness of vessels and obstruction of flow of blood; and one hesitant and forceful is indicative of stagnancy of Qi and blood stasis or persistent retention of phlegm or food which hinder Qi-blood from free circulation but vital Qi still strong.
Thready pulse, also called small pulse, is as thin as a silk thread, feeble, yet easily perceptible, usually indicating deficiency of both Qi and blood, and chronic deficiency syndromes, because inability of inadequate blood to replenish the vessels and failure of weak Qi to impel blood to flow.
If a thready and rapid pulse appears in cases with seasonal febrile disease, accompanied by coma and delirium, it indicates invasion of Ying (nutrient) system and Xue (blood) system or attack of the pericaridium by pathogenic heat.
A pulse, felt extremely soft, deep and thready, is called weak pulse seen in deficiency of both Qi and blood because of deficiency of blood leading to the thin and small shape of the pulse and weakness of Qi to the soft and deep shape.
A pulse that is felt full and forceful like waves surging, coming vigorously and going gently with a large volume, is called full pulse, usually indicating preponderance of pathogenic heat in Qi system.
A pulse with a wave, that lifts the finger tip to a greater height but does not tend to surge high as does full pulse, is called large pulse.
A pulse, large and forceful, suggests excess syndrome of pathogenic heat and one, large and weak, indicates deficiency syndrome marked by failure of vital Qi to be kept inside the body.
A taut pulse is one that feels straight and long, hard like the string of a musical instrument, usually seen in cases of the liver and gallbladder troubles, various pain syndromes, and retention of phlegm and fluid.
The liver keeps the free flow of Qi and this function must be noderate in normal conditions.
When pains and phlegm exist, the taut pulse, as the signs of the stagnation of Qi, may also appear.
It is also seen in malaria, consumptive disease or internal injury, insufficiency of Qi of middle-Jiao and attack of the spleen by hyperactive liver-Qi.
If a pulse feels taut, thready and rapid like the edge of a knife, it indicates a disease difficult to treat because of complete loss of the stomach-Qi.
However, if a soft, moderate and taut pulse often appears in a healthy person in spring it is considered as normal.
Pathogenic cold in the exterior often manifests itself by floating and tense pulse. and that in the interior by deep and tense pulse.
Yet a tense pulse also appears in cases of acute pain, or retention of indigested food.
An extremely taut and hollow pulse, giving the feeling just like touching the surface of a drum, is called tympanic pulse, often seen in patients with depletion of blood or spermatorrhea, abortion, metrorrhagia or metrostaxis, which all lead to outward floating of Qi resulting from exhaustion of essence and blood.
A slow and weak pulse pausing at regular intervals is called intermittent pulse, often seen in cases of visceral dysfunction, especially weakness of the heart-Qi giving rise to inability of the channel-Qi to continue regularly.
A pulse with short extent, only palpable at the Guan site but indistinct at Cun and Chi sites, is called short pulse, the condition of which is just opposite to a long pulse.
A short and forceful pulse which is formed by the obstricted channel-Qi to extend normally, indicates stagnation of Qi, blood stasis, and retentilon of phlegm or dyspepsia, while a short and weak pulse which is brought about by inability of weak Qi to promote blood flowing with vigour suggests consumption and deficiency of Qi.
For example, floating and tense pulse indicates exterior cold syndrome, and deep, thready and rapid pulse suggests interior heat sydnrome of deficiency type.
A pulse without the stomach-Qi, vitality and root is known as deteriorated pulse, indicative of the depletion 、of vital Qi of Zang-Fu organs and exhaustion of the stomach-Qi, usually seen at the stage of a patient's dying. Therefore, it is also known as moribund pulse.
Seven moribund, or fatal, pulses refer to the pulse conditions seen in critical cases, i. e, bubble--rising pulse, fish-swimming pulse, shrimp-darting pulse, roof-leaking pulse, bird-pecking pulse, rope-untying pulse and knocking-stone pulse.
This refers to a floating pulse beating like bubbles rising to the surface of boiling water, one of the ten moribund pulses.
This is one of the ten moribund pulses appearing in dying patients, which is hardly perceptible, like a swimming fish.
This refers to a quite slow and arrhythmic pulse ike the drops of rain passing through a leak of the roof, one of the ten moribund pulses, which indicates the exhaustion of the stomach-Qi.
A pulse beating with rapid, irregular rhythm and intervals like a bird pecking food, is called bird-pecking pulse, one of the ten moribund pulses, indicative of exhaustion of the spleen-Qi.
This is an irregular and rhythmless pulse resembing the untying of a knotted rope, one of the ten moribund pulses, which indicates depletion of both the kidney-Qi and Qi of Mingmen, or the gate of life.
A floating, full, rapid and replete pulse occurring in a newly-contracted or acute disease indicates that the pulse corresponds to the symptoms and the strong vital Qi can defeat the pathogens; while a deep, small, indistinct and weak pulse occurring in a recently-developed or acute disease suggests that the pulse does not correspond to the symptoms and the vital Qi has declined.
A deep. indistinct, thready and weak pulse appearing in a prolonged disease indicates that the pulse corresponds to the symptoms and the vital Qi recovers with retreat of the pathogens; while a floating, full, rapid, and replete pulse in a protracted disease indicates that the pulse does not correspond to the symptoms and the vital Qi declines without retreat of the pathogens.
Palpation is a diagnostic procedure by which a doctor can palpate his or her patient's skin, limbs, chest, abdomen and other affected regions of the body to detect local abnormal changes, thereby determining the location and nature of the disease.
The fever getting higher at the first palpation, but lower after a long press indicates heat-syndrome of superficies, and low fever at the beginning of press but higher after long palpation, heat-syndrome of the interior.
The swelling skin caved in after press with inability to recover immediately indicates edema, whereas the skin pit disappearing at once after the hand has been withdrawn is indicative of edema due to Qi stagnation.
In addition, by palpation the moisture, dryness of the skin and cutaneous and surgical diseases can also be detected.
By palpating the extremities a doctor is also able to differentiate diseases due to exogenous pathogens from those due to internal injury.
The fever in dorsal surface of the hands and feet is due to affection by exogenous pathogens; while the fever of palms and soles higher than that of the forehead, to internal injury.
This refers to a diagnostic method of palpating the Xuli area over the apex of the heart, where the pectoral Qi converges and the stomach-Qi accumulates.
Under normal conditions Xuli pulse is vigorous but not tense, moderate but not rapid, indicating accumulation of the pectoral Qi in the chest.
The small and weak Xuli pulse is due to internal insufficiency of pectoral Qi and the excessively strong Xuli pulse leading to vibration of the under-clothes of the patient suggests letting out of pectoral Qi.
For example, a feeling of epigastric pain, distension and rigidity upon pressure is referred to as a syndrome of agglomeration of pathogens in chest; while that of fullness in the epigastrium with softness and no pain sensation on pressure is described as a syndrome of fullness.
The mass found in the abdomen, hard and immovable, and with fixed pain belongs to the disease of the (blood) system due to blood stasis; whereas that appearing or disappearing alternatively, movable but without fixed pain, pertains to disease of the Qisystem due to stagnation of Qi.
Because acupoints are the small pools of the circulating Qi-blood of meridians in the superficies and the sites where Qi of Zang-Fu-organs passes through, palpation of acupoints provides us with information as to their changes and responses, thereby facilitating the diagnosis of diseases of some internal organs.
For example, floating and tense pulse indicates exterior cold syndrome, and deep, thready and rapid pulse suggests interior heat syndrome of deficiency type.
There can be observed symptoms of cold nature, such as cold limbs, clear urine, loose stool, pink tongue with whitish fur.
It is a method of differential diagnosis used to determine the location of pathological changes and the development tendency of a disease.
It refers to a syndrome caused by an attack of the superficies by six exogenous pathogens through the skin, hair, mouth and nose.
It is a syndrome contrary to the exterior one and is characterized by pathological changes of the internal organs caused by pathogens.
A patient with exterior syndrome may have such symptoms as fever, chilly sensation, thin fur of the tongue and floating pulse. If chilly sensation is replaced by aversion to heat, there may appear such symptoms as thirst, scanty dark urine, redness of the tongue with yellowish fur and rapid pulse, indicating that the disease has manifested itself by interior heat syndrome due to invasion of pathogenic agents from the superficial part of the body to the deep.
As excess of cold is the essence of the disease, the cold-syndrome in reality is treated by Tongmai Sini Tang of warm or hot nature, and the pseudo-heat symptoms will disappear by itself.
For example, in case of an interior syndrome due to interior heat, first appear restlessness, shortness of breath, cough and chest stuffiness, then fever and sweat.and the interior syndrome subsides with restlessness relieved or exthanthema developed, indicating that the pathogenic agent has been brought out.
It usually results from proper and prompt treatment and appropriate nursing, which help to build up body resistance.
For example, in late summer or early autumn, due to invasion by external pathogenic cold and internal pathogenic damp, there may appear symptoms characteristic of exterior syndrome, such as fever, chilly sensation, headache, and general aching, as well as symptoms characteristic of interior syndrome, such as epigastric stuffiness, anorexia, diarrhea, thick whitish fur of the tongue, etc.
For example, such syndromes as diarrhea due to indigestion, metrorrhagia and metrostaxis due to retention of stagnated blood in the interior and "fecal impaction due to heat with watery discharge" marked by accumulation of dry feces in the gastrointestinal tract with discharge of foul water etc., may be treated with purgative drugs to eliminate the interior-excess syndrome.
It is a method of differentiating the nature of a disease.
(2) In case of simultaneous occurrence of exterior and interior syndrome, it is marked by heat syndrome in the exterior with cold syndrome in the interior, or vice versa.
It refers to a change of the nature of a disease, i.e., conversion from cold syndrome to heat syndrom, or vice versa.
On the other hand. If a disease at its onset manifests itself by heat syndrome followed by cold syndrome, the former dies away as soon as the latter appears.
It denotes that the disease itself is of heat nature, but exhibits some cold symptoms, such as, cold limbs, deep pulse, etc.
The pateint may also have the following symptoms: excessive thirst, preference for cold drink, dry throat, foul breath, delirium, scanty dark urine, dry stool or dysentery of heat type with rectal tenesmus, dark reddish tongue with dry yellowish fur.
In this case, cold limbs and deep pulse are false appearances, while overabundant interior heat is essence of the disease.
It denotes that the disease itself is of cold nature, but exhibits some heat symptoms, such as fever, flushed face, thirst, and large pulse, It differs from heat syndrome in that the patient runs a fever, but has a desire for being covered up, he or she feels thirsty, but prefers to hot drinks, and his or her pulse is large, but weak.
It is a method of differential diagnosis used to determine the strength of vital Qi of the body and the virulence of pathogenic agents.
It refers to a morbid state manifested by deficiency of vital Qi, It may result from congenital defects and lack of proper care after birth, the latter being the main cause.
It refers to a morbid condition marked by exuberant pathogens.
It may result from rampancy of pathogens with vital Qi not declining, there by leading te an intense struggle between them.
Its main manifestations are: strong physical constitution. high fever, agitation, loud voice, abdominal distension, pain and tenderness, constipation, oliguria, rough pale tongue with thick and greasy fur, replete and forcetul pulse, etc.
It may be classified into three types: (1) Deficiency syndrome is dominant, complicated with excess symptoms. (2) Excess syndrome is predominant accompanied by deficiency symptoms. (3) Co-existence of excess syndrome and deficiency syndrome.
The disease is characterized by excess syndrome in its initial stage. Due to delayed treatment or misdiagnosis, it evolves into deficiency syndrome as a result of decline of pathogens and impairment of vital Qi during the protracted course of disease.
The disease is characterized by a deficiency syndrome in its early stage. Due to insufficiency of vital Qi, substantial pathogens gradually accumulate inside the body and give rise to some excess symptoms. This is known as excess syndrome due to deficiency syndrome.
Take, as another example, Qi deficiency in old people or excessive loss of blood in lying-in women. The former may impair the conducting function of the large intestine, while the latter may cause exhaustion of body fluid and dryness of the intestine, both of which may lead to excess syndrome manifested by constipation.
It is a syndrome of excess type characterized by accumulation of pathogens, but accompanied by symptoms similar to deficiency symdrome.
" For example, accumulation of heat or retention of phlegm and food in the stomach and intestines may lead to blockage of channels and stagnation of Qi and blood, giving 260. rise to symptoms simitar to deficiency syndrome, such as lassitude, chilliness and cold limbs, slow deep hidden pulse, etc.
Upon careful examination other symptoms may be found, such as loud voice, rough breath, deep and slow or hidden, but vigorous pulse, indicating that accumulation of pathogens in the interior is the real essence of disease, while symptoms similar to deficiency syndrome are merely false phenomena.
Pain with burning sensation is caused by the flow of pathogenic fire in collaterals or hyperactivity of fire due to Yin deficiency.
It has two connotations:(1) One refers to a syndrome as opposed to exterior syndrome of excess type due to invasion of body surface by pathogens, complicated with disharmony between nutritive Qi and defensive Qi and loose muscular striae.
Its clinical manifestations are: fever, aversion to wind, sweating, and slow floating pulse.
(2) The other connotation is that it is a condition of failure of superficial Qi to protect the body owing to deficiency of the spleen-Qi and lung-Qi.
As a result of Qi-deficiency and weakened superficies, the patient has spontaneous perspiration and is susceptible to an attack by exogenous pathogens.
It is a morbid state due to hypofunction of Zang-Fu organs, resulting from general debility due to protracted illness, senile debility, overstrain, improper diet, etc, manifested as dizziness, shortness of breath, disinclination to talk, low voice, lassitude, spontaneous perspiration, aggravation of the above symptoms on exertion, pale tongue, weak or feeble pulse.
It refers to a morbid condition of inability of Qi to lift, usually resulting from further development of Qi-deficiency.
Its clinical manifestations are: fainting, shortness of breath, lassitude, chronic diarrhea, abdominal distention with tenesmus, prolapse of the rectum, prolapse of the uterus, pale tongue with whitish fur, and weak pulse.
The main characteristics of Qi-collapse syndrome are symptoms of Qi-deficiency and ptosis of internal organs.
It refers to a morbid condition due to stagnation of Qi in a certain area or organ, resulting from functional disturbance of Zang-Fu organs and disorder of Qi as a result of emotional upset, improper diet and invasion by exogenous pathogens.
The main clinical manifestations of this syndrome are: distention, dis. tress and pain.
Qi-stagnation in different locations may give rise to different manifestations.
For example, stagnation of the liver-Qi is marked by hypochondriac distending pain, accompanied with emotional depression, frequent sighing, taut pulse; that of the stomach-Qi is manifested by epigastric distending pain; and that of the intestine-Qi is characterized by abdominal distention and wandering pain.
It refers to a morbid condition of adverse ascending of Qi due to its dysfunction.
It refers to a morbid condition due to deficiency of blood, resulting in failure to nourish Zang-Fu organs and channels.
It is a morbid condition resulting from coagulation of the extravasated blood in a certain region of the body which is not discharged or dissipated in time, or stagnation of blood due to its sluggish flow.
The common causes of the syndrome are: coagulation of cold, stagnation of Qi, deficiency of Qi, or trauma.
It refers to spontaneous bleeding. resulting from extravasation of blood due to exuberant heat within Zang-Fu organs and its attack on Xuefen (blood system) manifested as bleeding and symptoms indicative of blood heat, such as hematemesis, hemoptysis, hematuria, hematochezia,(all of which show) bright red blood, red tongue, and rapid pulse.
It is manifested by syndromes of both Qi-stagnation and blood stasis, such as restlessness, irritabihity, or emotional depression, bypochondriac distension and wandering pain, distending pain in the breast with masses, dysmenorrhea and discharge of dark purplish menses with clots in women, dark purplish tongue or ecchymosis over the tongue, and hesitant pulse. This syndrome is more frequently seen in females.
It refers to loss of blood due to deficiency of Qi, which results in inability to govern blood flow marked by hematemesis, hematochezia, epistaxis, metrorrhagia, lassitude, shortness of breath, pale complexion. pale tongue, and thready weak pulse.
It refers to a morbid condition of collapse of Qi after sudden massive hemorrhage, usually due to trauma, or metrorrhagia, or profuse bleedding after childbirth, manifested as suddenly ap. pearing pallor during profuse bleeding, cold limbs, profuse perspiration, even loss of consciousness, and hollow or indistinct pulse, or large but scattered pulse.
It is usually caused by profuse sweating, massive bleeding, severe vomiting, frequent diarrhea, polyuria. and consumption of body fluid due to excessive heat.
It refers to occurrence of phlegm syndrome provoked by an attack of wind-pathogen.
Its clinical manifestations are: feverish and restless sensation in the thorax, cough with thick yellowish sputum, or mania, or dry stool, or inflammation of the throat, yellowish greasy fur of the tongue, and rapid slippery pulse.
Its clinical manifestations are: chilliness and cold limbs, whitish, clear and thin phlegm, stabbing pain due to rheumatism involving the bone, inability to raise the limbs, whitish greasy fur of the tongue, deep slow pulse, or deep slippery pulse.
It is a syndrome marked by abundant expectoration accompanied by dampness manifestations.
It results from formation of phlegm-dampness due to hypofunction of the spleen, or affection by exogenous cold-dampness leading to disturbance of the spleen and stomach and especially dysfunction of the former with phlegm formed from accumulated dampness. Its clinical manifestations are: chest oppression and epigastric stuffiness, anorexia, vomiting, nausea, profuse expectoration, heaviness sensation in the limbs and sleepiness, thick greasy fur of the tongue, and slippery pulse.
It is a syndrome of phlegm accompanied by dryness manifestations, resulting from production of phlegm from accumulated body fluid due to dysfunction of the lungs which are impaired by pathogenic dryness or from burning and consumption of body fluid by exuberant heat with formation of phlegm.
Its clinical manifestations are: cough with little viscid and thick sputum not easily expectorated or with blood streaks, dry mouth and nasal cavity, dryness and pain of the throat, dry stool, dry tongue with little saliva, and thready slippery and rapid pulse.
It is a morbid condition due to fluid-retention in the stomach and intestines, manifested as fullness sensation in the chest, splashing sound in the stomach, vomiting clear thin saliva, dizziness, palpitation, shortness of breath, whitish slippery fur of the tongue, and taut slippery pulse.
It can be seen in gastric retention due to pyloric obstruction, intestinal obstruction due to dropsy, and functional disturbance of the stomach and intestines.
It is a syndrome of fluid-retention in the hypochondrium, manifested as pain over the hypochondriac region, which is aggravated by coughing or spitting, dragging pain upon turning over in bed or breathing, fullness sensation over the chest, shortness of breath, deep taut pulse, often seen in exudative pleuritis.
It is a morbid condition of accumulation of fluid in the subcutaneous tissue, manifested as heaviness and pain in the limbs, even edema, oliguria, or fever and aversion to cold, no sweat, cough with frothy sputum, whitish fur of the tongue, and taut tense pulse.
It is a mordid condition of accumulation of excessive fluid above the diaphragm manifested as oppressien sensaticn in the chest, shortness of breath, cough with dyspnea, difficulty in assuming a supine position, cough with whitish frothy sputum, fa, cial edema, whitish greasy fur of the tongue, and taut tense pulse.
It is a method of differential diagnosis to determine the pathogenesis, nature and site of a disease and the conflict between body resistance and pathogens based on the analysis and conprehension of the symptoms in light of the physiological functions and pathological manifestations of the Zang-Fu organs. As an important component of the differential diagnosis system, it serves as the basis of diagnosis for all clinical specialties of TCM.
This method, which lays the foundation for all other methods of differential diagnosis, includes differential diagnosis of Zang-organ diseases, of Fu-organ diseases, and of diseases of both Zang-organs and Fu-organs.
It refers to a morbid condition due to hyperactivity of the heart-fire in the interior, usually resulting from production of fire due to emotional upsets and stagnancy of Qi, or invasion of the interior by the pathogenic fire, or excessive intake of hot-natured food of acrid taste or warm-natured tonics, and manifested as dysphoria with feverish restless sensation in the thorax insomnia, flushed face, thirst, ulcers of the mouth and tongue, or difficult and painful urination with dark urine, hematuria or mania and delirium, redness of the tip of the tongue, or even rough and prickle-like fur of the tongue, and rapid forceful pulse.
It refers to impairment of consciousness caused by invasion of the heart by phlegm, usually resulting from production of phlegm due to emotional upsets, and stagnation of Qi, or coagulation of the pathogenic dampness in the heart, manifested as mental depression, apathy, aphrenia, soliloquy, improper behaviour, or sudden falling down with loss of consciousness, laryngeal rales, whitish greasy fur of the tongue, and slippery pulse.
It is a morbid condition of mental disturbance due to phlegm-fire, caused by emotional upsets, mental depression and anger, leading to stagnation of Qi and production of fire which transforms fluid into phlegm, or by invasion of the heart by pathogenic heat which converts fluid into phlegm.
Its clinical manifestations are: fever, raucous breathing, flushed face, congested eyes, expectoration of yellowish thick phlegm, laryngeal rales, delirium, red tongue with yellowish greasy fur, slippery rapid pulse, or insomnia, irritability, profuse sputum, feeling of oppression in the chest, dizziness, or paraphasia, and various manifestations of mania.
If the syndrome is caused by invasion by the pathogenic heat, the chief signs for differential diagnosis are high fever, abundant expectoration, and unconsciousness. If the syndrome is brought about by internal injury, the main ones for diagnosing mild cases are restlessness and insomnia, and those for diagnosing severe cases are mania.
It is a morbid condition of hypofunction of the lungs, usually resulting from impairment of the lung-Qi due to protracted illness and dyspneic cough, or insufficiency of Qi-production, marked by cough with dyspnea, shortness of breath aggravated on slight exertion, clear thin sputum, low weak voice, pale complexion, lassitude, or spontaneous perspiration, aversion to wind, susceptibility to cold due to exogenous pathogens, pale tongue with whitish fur, and feeble pulse.
It is a morbid condition due to invasion of the lungs by the wind-cold pathogen leading to obstruction of the lung-Qi, manifested by cough with whitish thin sputum, stuffy nose with watery discharge, slight aversion to cold, mild fever, no sweat, whitish fur of the tongue, and floating tense pulse.
It is a morbid condition of accumulation of the pathogenic cold in the lungs, manifested as cough with dyspnea, and thin whitish sputum, chilliness and cold limbs, pale tongue with whitish fur, and slow or moderated pulse.
Its clinical manifestations are: dyspnea, cough with thick yellowish sputum, high fever, thirst, irritability, even flaring of nares, chest pain, blood and pus-stained sputum with stinking smell, constipation, scanty dark urine, reddish tongue with yellowish fur, and slippery rapid pulse.
It is a syndrome due to affection by pathogenic dryness with impairment of fluid in the lungs in autumn, manifested as dry cough with no sputum or with scanty viscid sputum difficult to be expectorated, chest pain due to violent cough, dry mouth, lips, nose and throat, or fever, slight aversion to wind and cold, thin dry fur of the tongue, and thready rapid pulse.
It is a morbid condition of stagnation of phlegm-dampness in the pulmonary system, usually resulting from impairment of dispersing and descending function of the lungs due to attack by pathogenic cold and dampness or accumulation of phlegm-dampness due to impairment of the lungs by protracted cough and dysfunction of the lungs, or stagnation of phlegm in the lungs transformed from water-dampness due to inability of the spleen-Qi to transport body fluid.
Its clinical manifestations are: cough with copious whitish and thin sputum which is easily expectorated, feeling of oppression in the chest, of dyspnea, laryngeal rales, pale tongue with whitish greasy fur, taut and slippery or soft and floating pulse.
It is a syndrome due to invasion of the large intestine by damp-heat, usually resulting from retention of dampness and heat in the large intestine because of affection by exogenous damp-heat pathogen, or intake of unclean food.
Its clinical manifestations are: abdominal pain, diarrhea with purulent and bloody stool, tenesmus, or sudden onset of diarrhea with discharge of yellowish stinking stool, accompanied by burning sensation in the anus, dry mouth without desire for drink, scanty dark urine, or fever with or without aversion to cold, red tongue with greasy yellwish fur, soft and rapid, or slippery and rapid pulse.
Its clinical manifestation are: constipation (difficult defecation, even one bowel movement in several days), dry mouth and throat, dry red tounge, thready and hesitant pulse: often accompanied by halitosis, dizziness, etc.
This is a morbid state showing inability of the spleen to transport or transform nutrients due to insufficiency of the spleen-Qi usually caused by improper diet, fatigue, internal injury and consumption of the spleen-Qi by other acute of chronic disorders.
Its clinical manifestations are: poor appetite, abdominal distention aggravated after meals, diarrhea or loose stool, sallow complexion, shortness of breath, disinclination to talk due to mental fatigue, lassitude of limbs, pale tongue with whitish fur, slow and weak pulse.
It is a syndrome of inability of insufficient spleen-Qi to rise, resulting mostly from insufficiency of the spleen-Qi or from chronic diarrhea and dysentery, or overstrain.
It is often accompanied with shortness of breath, disinclination to talk, lassitude, dizziness, pale tongue with whitish fur and weak pulse.
It is mainly caused by injury to the spleen due to chronic disease or overfatigue.
Its clinical manifestation are: hemafecia, metrorrhagia, metrostaxis, hematuria, hematohidrosis, gingival hemorrhage; often accompanied with tassitude, shortness of breath, disinclination to talk, poor appetite, loose stool, pale complexion, pale tongue with whitish fur, and thready and weak pulse.
Its clinical manifestations are: epigastric distention and stuffiness, poor appetite, nausea, flat taste in the mouth, no thirst, abdominal pain, loose stool, heavy sensation in the head and body, or dim yellow complexion like being smoked, edema of the limbs, oliguria, pale swolen tongue with whitish and greasy fur and soft slow pulse.
Its clinical. manifestations are: abdominal distention, poor appetite, nausea, loose stool, yellowish urine, heavy sensation in the limbs, or bright orange complexion of the skin and sclera, irregular paroxysm of fever, not relieved by profuse sweating, red tongue with yellowish and greasy fur, and soft rapid pulse.
This is a syndrome due to stagnation of pathogenic cold in the stomach, usually caused by improper mode of living, exposure of the abdomem to cold, or excessive intake of raw or cold food.
Its clinical manifestations are: cold-pain in the epigastrium and abdomen - mild or severe, but relieved by warmth and aggravated by cold, flat taste in the mouth, absence of thirst; often accompanied with rumbling in the stomach, salivation, whitish and slippery fur of the tongue, slow or taut pulse.
It is a syndrome of excessive pathogenic heat in the stomach, caused by invasion of pathogenic fire as a result of excessive intake of acrid fatty and sweet food. stagnation of Qi or emotional depression, etc.
Its clinical manifestations are: burning pain in the epigastrium, gastric discomfort with acid regurgitation, thirst with desire for cold drinks, halitosis, vomiting immediately after meals, excessive appetite, inflamed, ulcerated or bleeding gums, constipation, scanty dark urine, red tongue with yellowish fur and slippery and rapid pulse.
This is a syndrome indicative of retention of food in the stomach due to its dysfunction in digesting food.generally caused by indigestion due to immoderate eating and drinking.
Its clinical manifestations include: epigastric distention and stuffiness or even pain, eructation with fout taste and smell, vomiting acid and rotten food with distention and pain relieved after vomiting. or flatulence, loose stool with acid, rotten and foul smelis, thick and greasy fur on the tongue and slippery pulse.
Its clinical manifestations are: dull pain of the epigastrium, hunger with disinclination to eat, belching, hiccup, dry mouth and throat, constipation, red tongue with thin dry fur, and thready rapid pulse.
It usually resuits from emotional depression, abrupt mental irritation and invasion by other pathogens.
Its clinical manifestations are: emotional depression, irritability, stuffiness in the chest, frequent sighing, wandering pain with distension in the chest, hypochondrium and lower abdomen; or sensation of foreign body in the throat which cannot be swallowed or coughed up, goiter, abdominal mass; in women distending pain in breasts, dysmenorrhea. and irregular menstruation. whitish fur on the tongue, and taut pulse.
It results mostly from an attack of fire due to emotional upsets, stagnation of liver-Qi and excessive intake of acrid, fatty and sweet food, and transformation of accumulated heat into fire.
This is a syndrome due to shortage of blood in the liver, resulting mostly from deficiency of both the spleen and kidneys, massive loss of blood or consumption of liver blood because of chronic disorders, Its clinical manifestations are: pallor, dizziness, tinnitus, dryness and discomfort of the eyes, poor sight, night blindness. numbness of the limbs. contracture of the tendons and muscles, muscular twitching, colorless nails; scanty light-colored menstrual discharge or even amenorrhea in females, pale tongue, and thready taut pulse.
(2) Syndrome of interior wind resulting from overabundance of heat This is a syndrome occurring in case of extreme hyparactivity of pathogenic heat.
Its clinical manifestations are: high fever, coma, restlessness, convalsion of the limbs, stiff neck, eyeballs turning upwards, lockjaw, or even opisthotonos, red or crimson tongue, and taut rapid pulse.
(3) Syndrome of interior wind caused by deficiency of blood This is a morbid condition due to lack of nourishment to the tendons and muscles owing to deficiency of blood stored in the liver.
For clinical manifestations refer to the section on "the syndrome of deficiency of the liver-blood".
This is a morbid condition due to retention of pathogenic dampness and heal in the liver and the gallbladder, mainly caused by the exogenous damp-heat pathogen or by the damp-heat pathogen produced by excessive intake of fatty, sweet and indigestible food or by accumulation of pathogenic dampness in the body which is transformed into heat due to dysfunction of the spleen in transporting.
This is a syndrome due to retention of pathogenic cold in the liver channel. resulting chiefly from invasion of the liver by pathogenic cold.
This is a morbid condition of attack by phlegm and heat due to dysfunction of the gallbladder in dispersion.
It results mainly from emotional upsets, depression of Qi, failure of the gallbladder to perform its dispersing function, and then production of phlegm and pathogenic heat due to stagnation of Qi.
Its clinical manifestations are: palpitation, insomnia, restlessness, stuffiness in the chest and distention of the hypochondrium, bitter taste, nausea, dizziness, yellow and greasy fur on the tongue, and taut slippery pulse.
It results mainly from kidney-deficiency in the aged, injury of the kidneys due to chronic disorders and intemperance in sexual life.
It is caused mainly by congenital defects, improper care after birth, or intemperance in sexual life and injury of the kidneys due to chronic disorders.
Its clinical manifestations are: in infants, retarded development, marked by microsoma low intelligence, bradypragia, tardy closure of fontanel, and dysostosis; in adults, sterility due to spermacrasia in males and due to amenorrhea in females, premature senility, baldness and odonteseisis, tinnitus, deafness, amnesia, trance, flaccidity of feet, hyponea and bradypragia.
This is a morbid condition due to retention of pathogenic damp-heat in the urinary bladder.
It usually results from the accumulation of exogenous damp-heat pathogen in the urinary bladder or downward flow to the urinary bladder of the damp-heat pathogen deriving from immoderate diet.
Its clinical manifestations are: Frequent and urgent micturition, scanty urine and dysuria, brownish red cloudy urine or hematuria, urinary calculus, often accompanied with fever and lumbago, red tongue with yellowish and greasy fur, and slippery rapid pulse.
Its clinical manifetetions are: Vexation, insomnia, palpitation, dizziness, tinnitus amnesia, soreness of the waist and knees, seminal emission, dysphoria with feverish sensation in the chest, palms and soles, dry throat and mouth, red tongue, thready and rapid pulse; sometimes accompenied with lassitude and feeling of cold in the loins and knees.
Its clinical manifestations are: aversion to cold, cold limbs, palpitation, dysuria, edema in the face and especially in the lower limbs, cyanotic lips and nails, pale, dark and cyanotic tongue with whitish and glossy fur, and deep thready and feeble pulse.
This is a morbid condition due to insufficiency of the heart-Qi and the lung-Qi.
It is usually brought about by overstrain or consumption of Qi in the heart and the lungs due to chronic cough with dyspnea.
Its clinical menifestations are: palpitation, shortness of breath, cough with dyspnea. thoracic stuffiness, weakness with spontaneous sweating especially on exertion, pallor or dark complexion, or even cyanotic lips, pale tongue with whitish fur and thready weak pulse.
It usuaily results from consumption of the lung-Qi and injury of the kidney-Qi by cough with dyspnea due to protracted illness.
Its clinical manifestations are: dyspnea, shortness of breath with prolonged exhalation and shortened inhalation, difficulty in breathing more obvious on exertion, spontaneous sweating, lassitude, leptophonia and shortness of breath. weakness of the loins and knees, pale tongue with whitish coating, deep and weak pulse, or severe dyspnea. cold limbs, cyanotic complexion, severe clammy sweat, and floating, large, unrooted pulse (easily felt on light pressure but disappearing on heavy pressure).
Its clinical manifestations are: pallor, aversion to cold, cold limbs, feeling of cold-pain in the waist, knees and lower abdomen, chronic diarrhea and dysentery, diarrhea before dawn or diarrhea with indigested food in the stool, dysuria, puffy face and edema of the limbs, severe abdominal distention resembling shape of a drum, pale and swollen longue with whitish and glossy fur, and deep weak pulse.
It usually results from deficiency of the jungs due to chronic cough with dyspnes which, in turn, affects the spleen, or from injury of the spleen due to improper diet and overstrain leading to its failure to transport essence to the lungs.
Its clinical manifestations are: protracted cough, shortness of breath with dyspnea, expectoration of profuse clear sputum, poor appetite, abdominal distention, loose stool, lassitude, debility with disinclination to talk, pallor, or even puffiness of face and feet, pale tongue with whitish fur, and thready weak pulse.
It results mostly rom impairment of the liver by emotional upsets and enduring anger leading to dysfunction of the liver which, in turn, affects the spleen's transporting function, or from impairment of the spleen by improper diet and overstrain leading to its deficiency which, in turn, gives rise to stagnation of pathogenic dampness in the body with the liver's function affected.
Its clinical manifestations are: distending and wandering pain in the chest and hypochondrium, sighing, emotional stress, irritability, poor appetite, abdominal distention, loose stool, borborygmus, flatulence, inclination to diarrhea due to abdominal pain ralieved after diarrhea whitish fur on the tongue, and taut pulse.
It usually results from emotional depression and the stagnation of hyperactive liver-Qi attacking the stomach transversely.
Its clinical manifestations are: chest stuffiness, distention and pain in the hypochondriac region and the epigastrium, hiccup, eructation, gastric discomfort with acid regurgitation, anxiety and irritability, whitish, yellowish and thin fur on the tongue, and taut pulse.
It results mainly from improper care after protracted illness, worries, fatigue, and chronic hemorrhage.
Its clinical manifestations are: Palpitation, insomnia, dreaminess, dizziness, amnesia, sallow complexion, poor appetite, abdominal distention, loose stool, lassitude and weakness, subcutaneous hemorrhage, scanty light coloured menstruation of a prolonged period, pale and tender tongue, and thready weak pulse.
Its clinical manifestations are: burning pain in the chest and hypochondrium, irritability, dizziness, conjunctival congestion, dysphoria with smothery sensation, bitter taste, paroxysmal cough or even hemoptysis, red tongue with yellow and thin fur and taut rapid pulse.
This is one of the methods of differential diagnosis for exopathic diseases, put forward in the book Shang Han Lunby Zhang Zhongjing, a distinguished physician in the Easten Han Dynasty.
When exogenous pathogens invade the body, the defensive Qi goes to the superficies to resist them and a conflict between the vital Qi (defensive Qi) and the pathogens ensues, thereby leading to fever. Since the defensive Qi has consumed on the superficies, it fails to warm the body and the symptom of aversion to cold appears as a result. As the defensive-Qi stimulates the pulse to the exterior it feels floeting.
Since the striae of the skin are loose, the pores will open during attack of the skin and muscles by pathogenic wind, thereby resulting in such symptoms as spontaneous sweating, floating and slow pulse.
Failure of the striae to open causes anhidrosis, which, in turn, results in obstruction of flow of the channel-Qi, and general aching occurs as a result.
And it is also the closure of striae of the skin that causes block and abnormal rising of lung-Qi, thereby leading to dyspnea.
The skin contracts while it is being attacked by the exopathogens, hence the pulse feels floating and tense.
Therefore, a syndrome characterized by closure of the striae of the skin and anhidrosis is also known as an exterior excess syndrome.
Its clinical manifestations are: high fever, profuse sweating, extreme thirst, full and large pulse, dysphoria, flushed face, yellow and dry fur on the tongue.
Spread of pathogenic heat all over the body brings about high fever, evaporation of internal heat forces body fluid to flow outward. thereby inducing profuse sweating, and overabundance of heat and profuse sweating, both of which consume body fluid, result in extreme thirst. When the excessive heat prompts the flow of Qi and blood in the body, the pulse will become full and large. Heat dislurbing mental activities causes dysphoria.
And finally, excessive heat steamingand consuming body fluid leads to yellow and dry fur on the tongue.
Its clinical manifestations are: afteroon fever, panhidrosis or polyhidrosis of handsand feel, abdominal distension with pain and tenderness, constipation of solid fecal material in the large intestinal tract or watery stool with a foul smell, restlessness, delirium, yellow, thick and dry fur on the. tongue, or even burnt black, fissured and prickly tongue, deep, slow and forceful pulse. Since the Qi of Yangming channel becomes most vigorous at the time Shen (or the period of a day from 3-5 p.m.), the internal pathogenic heat spreads quickly to the superficies, causing afternoon fever.
Its clinical manifestations are: bitter taste in the mouth, dry throat, dizziness, sensation of pain and fullness in the chest and hypochondrium, alternate attacks of chills and fever, taciturnity, poor appetite, vexation, vomiting, whitish or thin and yellowish fur on the tongue, and taut pusle.
When mental activities are affected by stagnation of fire, vexation ensues.
Its clinical manifestations are: persistent thirst, upward reflux of gas (Qi), chest pain with hot sensation, hunger with no desire for eating, cold limbs, diarrhea, vomiting or even vomiting of ascaris, and alternate spells of chills and fever.
If the fire is scorchingly fanned up by the pathogenic wind, the heat syndrome will show upward, causing persistent thirst and vomiting, and chest pain with hot sensation.
If there are ascaris in the intestinal tract, they will rise to the diaphragm, preferring warmth to cold, and will subsequently be vomited out.
Qi, Ying and Xue This is a diagnostic methed for epidemic febrile diseases by exopathogens, developed by Ye Tianshi, an eminent physician of the Qing Dynasty.
This theory was founded on the basis of differential diagnosis in accordance with the theory of six channels dealt with in the book Treatise on Febrile Diseases, and served as a supplement to that theory, thereby developing and enriching the theory for differential diagnosis and treatment of exopathic diseases in TCM.
The differential diagnosis by the analysis of Wei. Qi, Ying and Xue classifies all intricate clinical manifestations in the course of epidemic febrile diseases into four categories: Weifen, Qifm, Yingfen and Xuefen syndromes, which denote the four different stages (superficial or deep and mild or serious) in the development of an epidemic febrile disease.
It is also thought of a law governing the development and changes of epidemic febrile diseases due to exopathogens.
Initial consumption of body fluid by the pathogenic heat brings about dry mouth and slight thirst, and invasion of the skin by the pathogenic heat, whereby the lungs fail to perform their dispersing and descending function, Tesults in cough.
When the throat, as an outlet of the lungs, is scorched by the warm-heat pathogen, it will become swollen and painful.
Its clin. ical manifestations are: fever, aversion to heat rather than cold, red tongue with yellowish fur, rapid pulse; often accompanied by vexation, thirst, scanty dark urine, etc.
In case of stagnation of the pathogenic heat in the lungs such symptoms occur as cough, dyspnea, chest pain and cough with yellowish thick sputum; In case of affection of the chest and diaphragm by the pathogenic heat, there may appear such symptoms as vexation, heartburn and restlessness, In case of invasion of the stomach by the pathogenic heat, there may occur such symptoms as high fever. profuse sweating, extreme thirst, and large full pulse. In case of accumulation of pathogenic heat in the intestinal tract such symptoms as constipation or constipation of solid fecal material with watery. discharge, fullness, pain and hard sensation in the abdomen, yellow, thick and dry fur on the tongue, and deep. replete and forceful pulse are likely to occur.
To sum up, all symptoms and signs resulting from attack of the interior from the superficies by the pathogenic heat with Yingfen and Xuef en unaffected belong to the category of Qifen syndrome.
This is a critical syndrome indicating invasion of Xuefen by the warm-heat pathogen, which is regarded as the last and most serious stage of an epidemic febrile disease, clinically characterized by invasion of blood by excessive heat and disorder of mental activities.
Clinical manifestations indicate fever, restlessness, coma, delirium, purple or dark skin eruptions, hemoptysis. epistaxis, hematochezia, convulsion and syncope. reddened or crimson tongue, thready and rapid pulse.
Fever is the result of invasion of Xuef en by the pathogenic heat.
In case of mental disorder due to heat, such symptoms as restlessness, coma and delirium are likely to occur.
Finally, reddened or crimson tongue, and small rapid pulse are characteristic of the morbid condition in which Xuefen is fumed and scorched by the pathogenic heat.
This is a method of differential diagnosis for epidemic febrile diseases, invented by Wu Tang, a distinguished physician of the Qing dynasty.
Epidemic febrile disease is a general term for all acute febrile diseases caused by different warm-heat pathogens in the four seasens. With seasonal climates, types of exopathogens and the patient's constitution and bodily response.epidemic febrile diseases vary widely in their form, each having its own distinguishing characteristics.
In brief, differential diagnosis in light of the doctrine of tri-Jiao is a theory about the development of epidemic febrile diseases from the upper part to the lower part of the body, and a further supplement to the differential diagnosis by the analysis of Wei, Qi, Ying and Xue as well.
This is an exterior syndrome due to invasion of the body by the damp-heat pathogen at the early stage of an epidemic febrile disease.
Its clinical manifestations are: severe aversion to cold, slight or no fever or afternoon fever, heavy sensation even the head as if tightly bound, heavy sensation in the limbs, lassitude, anhidrosis, chest distension and stuffiness in the epigastrium, poor appetite, sticky taste in the mouth with no feeling of thirst, hyponea, borborygmus, loose stool, whitish and greasy fur on the tongue, and soft, slow pulse.
This is a syndrome due to invasion of the body by damp-heat pathogen at the middle stage of an epidemic febrile disease, the main pathogenesis of which lies in the retention of the damp-heat pathogen in the spleen and stomach.
Its clinical manifestations are: moderate fever which is higher in the afternoon and does not subside after sweating, heavy sensation in the limbs, lassitude, chest stuffiness and abdominal distention, nausea, poor appetite. thirst with little desire for drink, sallow or yellowish complexion, hyponea, hypologia or coma, scanty dark urine, loose stool, sudaminal crystallina, greyish and yellowish fur on the tongue and soft rapid pulse.
This is a syndrome due to stagnation of the damp-heat pathogens extending from the middle-Jiao to the lower-Jiao in the urinary bladder and the large intestine, leading to dysfunction of the former in micturition and functional disturbance of the latter.
Its clinical manifestations are: dysuria or scanty dark urine, thirst with desire for little drink, constipation, feeling of hardness and fullness in the lower abdomen, or loose stool with tenesmus. sensation of distension over the head.dizziness, greyish, yellowish and greasy fur on the tongue, and soft, rapid pulse. Principles
It refers to principles that must be followed in the prevention and treatment of disease.
"Preventive treatment of disease"involves prevention of a disease before it actually occurs and control of an existing disease. That is the principle of preventing the occurrence and development of disease in TCM.
Therefore, recuperating one's vigour to keep a sound mind, taking exercise to build up one's health.leading a regular and temperate life, preventing disease with medicines, and artificial immunity can all increase body resistance.
In addition, developing hygienic habits, preventing pollution of the environment, water supply and food can also guard against invasion of pathogens.
Once it occurs, a disease should be early diagnosed and treated and be cured in its initial stage, so as to stop it from developing into a more serious state.
That is to say, hyperfunction of the liver (wood) may affect the functioning of the spleen (earth). Therefore, disorder of the liver is often clinically treated in combination with treatment for strengthening the spleen and stomach in. order to make them strong enough to resist liver-pathogens. That is a practical application of the principle regarding control of the development of an existing disease.
They are laws which must be followed in the treatment of disease.
They comprise certain concrete medical treatment, namely, diaphoresis, emisis, purgation, regulation, warming, heat-clearing, invigoration, resolution, etc.
The therapeutic method is different from the therapeutic principle in that the latter is the general principle guiding the therapeutic method, while the former is the practical application of the therapeutic principle.
In handling a disease a doctor must search for its primary cause, in accordance with which he or she may adopt a proper treatment.
Thorefore, in treating a disease a doctor must be adept at finding out the cause of a disease, and analysing its pathogenesis, thereby instituting a treatment accordingly. Take headache as an example.
Headache due to exopathy is of wind-cold type in etiology and, therefore, treatment by relieving the exterior syndrome with drugs pungent in flavor and warm in nature is advisable, while headache due to exopathy of wind-warm type should be treated by relieving the exterior syndrome with drugs pungent in flavor and cool in nature.
This is what is meant by treatment aiming at the primary cause of disease.
It is a commonly used therapeutic principle of treating a disease with the method and drugs contrary to its nature, or manifestations. Here, it refers to a method of treating a disease with recipes and drugs opposite to its extrinsic phenomena.
It is suitable to those cases in which manifestations of a disease accord with its nature. Therefore, treatment contrary to symptoms and signs of a disease is in fact one in accordance with its nature.
Since the manifestations of most diseases coincide with their nature, routine treatment has been a therapeutic principle most commonly used clinically.
Consequently, treatment of cold syndromes with medicines of hot nature, that of heat syndromes with medicines of cold nature, that of deficiency syndromes by reinforcement, and that of excess syndromes by purgation, all are examples of routine treatment.
It refers to a therapy of cold-syndrome with drugs of hot nature, which is suitable to interior cold syndrome of excess type of a cold disease manifested by cold signs.
It is a therapeutic method for treating heat-syndrome, with drugs of cold nature, which is suitable to excess-heat type of a febrile-disease manifested by heat signs.
For example, such syndromes as high fever, aversion to heat, excessive thirst, profuse sweating and full and large pulse etc. caused by an attack of pathogenic heat (fire) on the human body should be treated by clearing the pathogenic.heat and purging pathogenic fire with drugs bitter in taste and cold in nature.
It is a therapy for various types of asthenia-syndromes, applicable to a deficiency case manifested by asthenia-signs.
It is a therapeutic method for treating excess syndromes, applicable to an excess case manifested by excess signs.
For instance, retention of pathogenic heat in the stomach and intestines marked by such symptoms as fever, fullness and pain in the abdomen, constipation etc., should be treated by purgation to remove the retained indigested food in the gastrointestinal tract.
The false appearances of a disease are phenomena that distort or reverse its nature and are unable to represent its essence.
Therefore, in treating a disease we must see through its appearances to get at its essence. Treatment contrary to the routine appears to conform with the false signs of a disease, but actually it is contrary to its essence.
As a consequence, treatment contrary to the routine as well as routine treatment are both practical application of the therapeutic principle of treating a disease by aiming at its primary cuses.
Treatment of pseudo-heat syndrome with drugs of hot nature, that of pseudo-cold syndrome with drugs of cold nature, that of the obstructive disease with tonics, that of discharging disease with purgatives, etc, all these treatments are examples of this therapeutic principle.
Since excess of heat is the essence of the disease, the heat-syndrome must be treated with drugs of cold-cool nature, and subsequently the false manifestations or pseudo-cold symptoms will disappear by itself.
This is what is meant by treatment of psseudo-cold syndrome with drugs of cold nature.
It is applicable to treatment of such deficiency-syndrome in reality with pseudo-excess symptoms as obstruction syndrome due to deficiency.
For example, the patient with insufficiency of the spleen, who usually presents wit! remittent abdominal and epigastric distention, anorexia, pale tongue and feeble and weak pulse, etc, but develops no such symptoms as dyspepsia, stagnation of phlegm-dampness should be treated with drugs for strengthening the spleen and replenishing Qi.
When the spleen-Qi functions properly in transport. the abdominal distention will subside by itself.
It is a method of treating excess-syndrome with discharging symptoms including excess-syndrome in reality with pseudo-deficiency symptoms, with purgative drugs.
Invasion of blood by cold pathogens leads to coagulation due to blood-cold; invasion of blood by heat pathogens leads to sticky stagnation.
The soft, even and forceful pulse indicates the vitality of stomach-Qi.
In other words, any disease has its primary and secondary cause. So far as, pathogens and vitalQi are concerned, the latter is primary while the former secondary.
As regards the sequence of diseases the original or preceding disease is primary while the newly-developed, accompanying one is secondary. Frequently, there is a difference between the primary and the secondary, the principal and the subordinate in complicated and changeable cases, and so is there with order of priority in the treatment of a disease.
In general, in an urgent case treatment aims at relieving the predominant symptoms (the secondary) first. In a chronic case, however, treatment aims at removing its primary cause (the primary).
Therefore, in treating a disease, the relationship between Qi and blood must be regulated to restore their coordination according to the principle of "eliminating what is in excess and make up for what is lacking".
In this case, it is advisable to relieve the primary disease, or treat the original or old disorder according to its cause and pathogenesis.
Since both the primary and the secondary aspects are not too critical, it is advisable to suplement Qi and expel exogenous pathogens, with the former aiming at relieving the primary disorder and the latter at relieving the secondary one.
In so doing, invasion and affection by pathogens can be warded off and vital Qi be preserved and restored.
Therefore, eliminating pathogens, like supporting vital Qi, is also one of the important principles underlying clinical therapy.
Eliminating pathogens can be achieved mostly by the use of purgative method for excess syndrome, which is applicable to excess syndromes, in which invasion by pathogens is the primary contradiction and vital Qi has not been on the decline yet.
However, the actual therapeutic method employed for this purpose varies greatly with different pathogens and with different sites of their invasion.
For example, in case of attack of the superficies by exuberant exogenous pathogens, diaphoretic therapy is indicated; in case of invasion of the upper part of the chest by pathogens, accompanied by accumulation of abundant sputum and saliva, or prolonged retention of food in the gastrointestinal tract, or food poisoning, it is advisable to apply emetic therapy; in case of invasion of the lower part of the gastrointestinal tract by pathogens with pathogenic heat combined with waste products in the intestines, purgation is practiced; in case of sthenic heat-syndrome and sthenic fire-syndrome, heat-clearing and fire-purging therapy is applied; in case of cold-syndrome it is advisable to eliminate pathogenic cold by warming the middle-Jiao; and in case of dampness syndrome it is better to dispel pathogenic dampness by promoting diuresis. In addition, phlegm must be resolved, whenever it is found to exist, and blood stasis, whenever it is detected, be removed by promoting blood circulation.
This is a therapeutic approach with support of vital Qi as the dominant factor, supplemented by elimination of pathogens, which is applicable to asthenia-syndrome accompanied by sthenia-syndrome with the former as the major trouble.
For example, the insufficiency of the spleen with overabundance of dampnees, which is asthenia-syndrome accompanied with sthenia-syndrome caused by dysfunction of the spleen in transport due to its insufficiency resulting in the production of phlegm-dampness in the body, should be treated mainly by invigorating the spleen to support vital Qi, supplemented by removing phlegm-dampness to eliminate pathogens. This is how this approach works.
It is indicated in sthenia-syndrome accompanied by a sthenia-syndrome with excessive pathogens as the main trouble.
For example, some patients with malnutrition due to parasitic infestation should first be treated by invigorating the spleen to support vital Qi because the latter is too weak to tolerate parasiticidal therapy. Only after vital Qi is restored to its normal condition, can parasiticidal therapy with removing food-stagnancy be employed.
In this case if treatment of supporting vital Qi is simultaneously applied, contrary to what is expected, pathogens may be encouraged and left in the body.
For example, the syndrome of metrorrhagia and metrostaxis due to obstruction of stagnated blood in the interior leading to deficiency of vital Qi because of loss of blood is not easy to stop and a therapy for invigoration is of no help either, jf blood stasis is not removed.
Similarly, in treating disorders of other Zang-Fu organs we should make every effort to regulate the relationship between all Zang-Fu organs, enabling them to coordinate each other in functioning on the basis of the theory of their physiological interconnection and pathological interaction. Only in so doing can good results be achieved..
Qi serves as the commander of blood, which, in turn, acts as the mother of Qi, this referring to a close relation between them.
When this interaction between them ceases to function, various disorders due to incoordination between them may ensue.
For instance, in case of deficiency of blood or deficiency of both Qi and blood resulting from insufficient blood formation due to deficiency of Qi (the function of which is to produce blood), treatment should be aimed mainly at invigorating Qi supplemented by replenishing blood; in case of blood stasis resulting from deficiency or stagnation of Qi (the function of which is to promote blood circulation), also known as blood stasis due to deficiency of Qi or blood stasis due to stagnation of Qi, treatment be aimed at invigorating Qi to promote blood circulation or at promoting the flow of Qi to activate blood circulation, thereby dissipating blood stasis; in case of syncope or hemoptysis and hematemesis due to bleeding resulting from adverse rising of Qi as a result of its functional disturbance, it is necessary to regulate blood flow by sending down adversely ascending Qi; in case of hemorrhage due to deficiency of Qi which fails to control blood flow, it is advisable to control blood flow by invigorating Qi; and in case of exhaustion of Qi resulting from massive hemorrhage (because deficiency of blood, the mother of Qi, leads to insufficiency of Qi), it is essential to arrest bleeding by invigorating Qi in acute cases on the basis of the principle of treating blood collapse by first supplementing Qi.
The occurrence, development and termination of a disease are influenced by various factors, such as climatic and geograhphico-environmental conditions, and constitutional factors of an individual in particular.
Therefore, in treating a disease, we must take into consideration all factors contributing to it, to make a concrete analysis of concrete conditions and deal with them in different ways, thereby working out a proper method of treatment.
Consequently administration of different drugs to different patients according to different seasons and climates is known as treatment in accordance with seasonal conditions.
For example, the common cold in the northwest severely cold area is always treated with drastic sudorifics in large doses such as Chinese ephedra Herba Ephedrae and cassia (twig) Ramulus, etc. In the southeast warm area, however, it is treated usually with drugs Herba Schizonetae and Radix Ledebourielle with mild effect and in smaller doses. Drugs such as Chinese ephedra Herba Ephedrae and cassia (twig) Ramulus are rarely prescribed.
In consequence, administration of different drugs to different patients according to different localities is known as treatment in accordance with local conditions.
For example, an old person differs from a child not only in age but also in physiological functions and pathological manifestations.
The former due to deficiency of Qi and blood and decline of physiological functions often suffers from deficiency-syndrome or asthenia-syndrome accompanied by sthenia-syndrome.
In this case, therapy for invigoration is indicated. In case of excessive pathogens to be eliminated, purgative drugs should be prescribed with great caution and in doses smaller than those for young people or people during their prime.
The latter, who due to exuberant vitality, inadequacy of Qi and blood and delicate and tender Zang-Fu organs is susceptible to cold or heat, to asthenia or sthenia, suffers from a disease with a rapid progress.
It refers to a morbid condition due to insufficiency of Qi and blood and abnormality of their respective physiological functions and dysfunction of their interdependence and interaction as well.
As a consequence, this therapeutic principle, whereby treatment is prescribed, taking into account the human body as a whole and individual differences among different persons, is referred to as treatment in accordance with physique of an individual.
